ty) and “opportunism” (self-interest with guile). The greater the investment in capital-intensive facilities and the greater the optimized size of these facilities, the greater the incentive companies have for insurance against cost increases. Thus, the more concentrated the facilities of production and supply, the more likely the integration of the two within a single enterprise.</p>', '<p>According to the passage, which of the following is the most frequent motive for vertical integration?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ09', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (C). &nbsp;Choices (A) and (E) offer motives for horizontal combination, and (B) describes a benefit that may result if horizontal combination is handled correctly. Choice (D) names an end that is related neither to vertical integration nor to horizontal combination. Reread the last paragraph: “More often, however, the motive was to ensure a steady supply of materials into the enterprise\'s production, which maintained the cost advantages of scale and scope. It provided insurance against cost increases from fluctuating production, and reduced the cost of inventory storage and other carrying costs.” This is explicitly reflected in choice (C), the correct answer.</span></p>', 1001),
