ty) and “opportunism” (self-interest with guile). The greater the investment in capital-intensive facilities and the greater the optimized size of these facilities, the greater the incentive companies have for insurance against cost increases. Thus, the more concentrated the facilities of production and supply, the more likely the integration of the two within a single enterprise.</p>', '<p>The main purpose of the passage is to analyze:</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ10', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (A). &nbsp;The passage compares, in detail, the motives behind and effects of vertical integration and horizontal combination. Choice (B) is incorrect because incentives in mergers are mentioned only with respect to horizontal combination. The answer is too narrow to accurately reflect the breadth of the passage. Choice (C) is wrong because the feasibility of increased output is not explicitly discussed and would be too narrow to describe the entire passage. Choice (D) explains one motive for vertical integration and is also too narrow. Choice (E) alludes to the risks outlined in the final paragraph, but has no bearing on the passage as a whole. The correct answer is choice (A).</span></p>', 1001),
(1371, 0, 136239, 'verbal', '<p>Often, the incentive for the acquisition or merger of competitive enterprises producing similar products was to gain more effective control of output, price, and markets. Such horizontal combination increased organizational capabilities only if a single, centralized administrative control was established over the acquired companies, and then the facilities and personnel were restructured to exploit the economies of scale and scope. If the administrations of the acquired companies were not centralized, but operated autonomously as they had before the change, the enlarged enterprise remained little more than a federation of firms. The resulting cost advantages were minimal. The motivations behind vertical integration — that is, growth through obtaining facilities along the chain of production — were more complex. Faster “throughput,” cost reductions, and increased productivity in terms of worker output rarely resulted from vertical integration unless the additional processes were directed to the firm’s existing ones by its own rails or pipes. Such integration was particularly successful in the production of metals and machinery. Where the facilities to make related products were located at a distance, increased “throughput” was less feasible. The motivation for such investments in growth by vertical integration was primarily defensive, but not in the same way as with horizontal combination. Sometimes the aim was to withhold supplies from competitors, thereby creating barriers to entry. More often, however, the motive was to ensure a steady supply of materials into the enterprise’s production, which maintained the cost advantages of scale and scope. It provided insurance against cost increases from fluctuating production, and reduced the cost of inventory storage and other carrying costs. It lowered the risk that suppliers would fail to carry out contractual agreements — risks economists have termed “bounded rationality” (human fallibility) and “opportunism” (self-interest with guile). The greater the investment in capital-intensive facilities and the greater the optimized size of these facilities, the greater the incentive companies have for insurance against cost increases. Thus, the more concentrated the facilities of production and supply, the more likely the integration of the two within a single enterprise.</p>', '<p>Based on information from the passage, which action would an economist classify as “behavioral risk,“ the impact of which might be minimized by vertical integration?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ11', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (B). &nbsp;Behavioral risk has been termed “bounded rationality“ and “opportunism.“ &nbsp;A customer who fails to pay invoices is exploiting the company. This kind of risk could be minimized by vertical integration (the company would own the customer). &nbsp;The other answer choices do not address either “human fallibility“ or “self-interest with guile,“ nor do they represent risks that would be minimized by vertical integration.</span></p>', 1001),
(1372, 0, 301496, 'verbal', '', '<p>While the mounting circumstantial evidence against him seemed rather damning, the results of the DNA testing _______________ him entirely.</p>', 2, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ12', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answers are exonerated and exculpated. &nbsp;The while at the beginning of the sentence indicates a contradiction, so although he appears guilty, he is not. &nbsp;Because both exonerate and exculpate mean "to free from blame", they are correct.  To exacerbate is to make worse, and elocute refers to well-done speech, so neither applies here. Elude means "to avoid," and exterminate is "to kill," so these are incorrect.</span></p>', 1001),
(1373, 0, 680671, 'verbal', '', '<p>When his family raised legitimate concerns about his outlandish behavior, his defensive retort was that they failed to appreciate the _____________________ affectations that he painstakingly acquired to keep the family name in the public eye.</p>', 2, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ13', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited answers are peculiar and idiosyncratic,Because the behavior is outlandish and the family is concerned, the behavior clearly stands out in a way that the family does not appear to approve of, making peculiar and idiosyncratic the answers, since both indicate the unconventional. &nbsp;Orthodox means conventional, and fettered is limited or restrained, so neither applies here. Interminable suggests that the behavior is never-ending, so that does not fit the sentence; nor does resplendent, which suggests brilliance</span></p>', 1001),
(1374, 0, 438579, 'verbal', '', '<p>America\'s industrial history is dotted with _______________ geniuses who, without formal schooling, laboratories, etc., invented machines both efficient and brilliant.</p>', 2, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ14', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited answers are eccentric and unconventional,Eccentric means "unconventional, and slightly strange." &nbsp;Both words fit the context well with nearly the same meaning.</span></p>', 1001),
(1375, 0, 168123, 'verbal', '', '<p>Einstein was continually pondering the impossibility of fixing absolute position, absolute time.  The theory of relativity was not discovered as much as it was ________________ slowly in the course of studious examination of many strands of </p>', 2, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ15', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited answers are developed and evolved,The sentence describes a slow, not sudden, process. &nbsp;The two best words for that description, which also encompass progress over time, are developed and evolved. &nbsp;All the other words convey a meaning of sudden revelation</span></p>', 1001),
(1376, 0, 309390, 'verbal', '<p>Some authors have challenged the common perception of the Italian Renaissance as a time of creativity and positive change.  For example, the Dutch historian Johan Huizinga argued that the Renaissance caused the death of the Latin language because cultural leaders insisted on using the archaic, classical form of Latin.</p>', '<p>It can most reasonably be inferred from the passage that</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ16', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"><span class="Apple-tab-span">&nbsp;</span></span><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (A). &nbsp;The question asks you to find the statement that can be inferred from the information given in the passage. &nbsp;The passage informs us that some authors are challenging commonly held ideas about the Renaissance, and then provides an example: one author’s take on how the Renaissance affected Latin. &nbsp;Inference questions are essentially must be true questions; first assume everything in the passage is true, and then find the one answer choice that must also be true based on the information in the passage. &nbsp;In this case, assuming the passage to be true doesn’t make any of choices (B), (C), (D) or (E) have to be true.  The statements contained in (D) and (E) have no foundation in the passage at all, while saying that the Renaissance killed Latin is not the same as saying Latin would still be alive were it not for the Renaissance, as in choice (B). &nbsp;Choice (C) can be eliminated because while the leaders of the Renaissance insisted on use of the classical form of Latin, that doesn\'t necessarily mean the classical form was preferred.  It may have been preferred by leaders of the Renaissance but not by the populace as a whole.  Or, the leaders of the Renaissance may not have preferred it, but rather felt some obligation to promote it (perhaps because of tradition, or because the Pope demanded it). &nbsp;We simply can\'t tell from the passage.  </span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Choice (A) is the best choice. &nbsp;If the Renaissance brought about the death of Latin, it follows logically that there was something alive to kill, namely, a living Latin language at the beginning of the Renaissance</span></p>', 1001),
(1378, 0, 213672, 'verbal', '<p>When we come to the vowel changes in Modern English we see the importance of the factors that determined the length of vowels in Middle English.  All Middle English long vowels underwent extensive alteration in passing into Modern English, but the short vowels, in accented syllables, remained comparatively stable.  If we compare Chaucer\'s pronunciation of the short vowels with ours, we note only two changes of importance, those of a and u.  By Shakespeare\'s day (i.e. at the close of the sixteenth century) Chaucer\'s a had become an [æ] in pronunciation (cat, thank, flax).  In some cases this Middle English a represented an Old English æ (at, apple, back) and the new pronunciation was therefore a return to approximately the form which the word had in Old English.  It is the usual pronunciation in America and a considerable part of southern England today.  The change which the u underwent was what is known as unrounding.  In Chaucer\'s pronunciation this vowel was like the u in full.  By the sixteenth century it seems to have become in most words the sound which we have in but (e.g., cut, sun; love, with the Anglo-Norman spelling of o  for u).  As far as the short vowels are concerned it is clear that a person today would have little difficulty in understanding the English of any period of the language.</p>', '<p>According to the passage, which of the following is true of Modern English?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ17', '<p ><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"><span class="Apple-tab-span">&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (B). Choices (A), (C), and (E) are conclusions not found in the passage. &nbsp;There is no support for choice (C).</span></p>', 1001),
(1379, 0, 805028, 'verbal', '<p>When we come to the vowel changes in Modern English we see the importance of the factors that determined the length of vowels in Middle English.  All Middle English long vowels underwent extensive alteration in passing into Modern English, but the short vowels, in accented syllables, remained comparatively stable.  If we compare Chaucer\'s pronunciation of the short vowels with ours, we note only two changes of importance, those of a and u.  By Shakespeare\'s day (i.e. at the close of the sixteenth century) Chaucer\'s a had become an [æ] in pronunciation (cat, thank, flax).  In some cases this Middle English a represented an Old English æ (at, apple, back) and the new pronunciation was therefore a return to approximately the form which the word had in Old English.  It is the usual pronunciation in America and a considerable part of southern England today.  The change which the u underwent was what is known as unrounding.  In Chaucer\'s pronunciation this vowel was like the u in full.  By the sixteenth century it seems to have become in most words the sound which we have in but (e.g., cut, sun; love, with the Anglo-Norman spelling of o  for u).  As far as the short vowels are concerned it is clear that a person today would have little difficulty in understanding the English of any period of the language.</p>', '<p>In the conclusion of the passage, the author is concerned primarily with:</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ18', '<p ><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (D). Choice (A) is almost accurate, but the author was only discussing short vowels when he made the "little difficulty" comment. &nbsp;Choice (B) might appeal to anyone who did not read the paragraph closely, but it is not supported.  Choice (C) is false because he didn\'t need to vindicate anything, and choice (E) goes too far. This leaves choice (D), which correctly summarizes his conclusion.</span></p>', 1001),
(1380, 0, 326129, 'verbal', '<p>When we come to the vowel changes in Modern English we see the importance of the factors that determined the length of vowels in Middle English.  All Middle English long vowels underwent extensive alteration in passing into Modern English, but the short vowels, in accented syllables, remained comparatively stable.  If we compare Chaucer\'s pronunciation of the short vowels with ours, we note only two changes of importance, those of a and u.  By Shakespeare\'s day (i.e. at the close of the sixteenth century) Chaucer\'s a had become an [æ] in pronunciation (cat, thank, flax).  In some cases this Middle English a represented an Old English æ (at, apple, back) and the new pronunciation was therefore a return to approximately the form which the word had in Old English.  It is the usual pronunciation in America and a considerable part of southern England today.  The change which the u underwent was what is known as unrounding.  In Chaucer\'s pronunciation this vowel was like the u in full.  By the sixteenth century it seems to have become in most words the sound which we have in but (e.g., cut, sun; love, with the Anglo-Norman spelling of o  for u).  As far as the short vowels are concerned it is clear that a person today would have little difficulty in understanding the English of any period of the language.</p>', '<p>What is the most likely reason that the author frequently cites Chaucer?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ19', '<p ><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (E). &nbsp;Choices (B) and (C) are irrelevant and would also require special knowledge to confirm. &nbsp;If choice (A) were true, the author\'s use of Chaucer would be entirely different than it is. &nbsp;Choice (D) makes Shakespeare the reason for the author\'s use of Chaucer, which cannot be substantiated from the passage. &nbsp;Choice (E) best explains the author\'s use of Chaucer without requiring special knowledge of the subject.</span></p>', 1001),
(1381, 0, 897577, 'verbal', '<p>When we come to the vowel changes in Modern English we see the importance of the factors that determined the length of vowels in Middle English.  All Middle English long vowels underwent extensive alteration in passing into Modern English, but the short vowels, in accented syllables, remained comparatively stable.  If we compare Chaucer\'s pronunciation of the short vowels with ours, we note only two changes of importance, those of a and u.  By Shakespeare\'s day (i.e. at the close of the sixteenth century) Chaucer\'s a had become an [æ] in pronunciation (cat, thank, flax).  In some cases this Middle English a represented an Old English æ (at, apple, back) and the new pronunciation was therefore a return to approximately the form which the word had in Old English.  It is the usual pronunciation in America and a considerable part of southern England today.  The change which the u underwent was what is known as unrounding.  In Chaucer\'s pronunciation this vowel was like the u in full.  By the sixteenth century it seems to have become in most words the sound which we have in but (e.g., cut, sun; love, with the Anglo-Norman spelling of o  for u).  As far as the short vowels are concerned it is clear that a person today would have little difficulty in understanding the English of any period of the language.</p>', '<p>Which of the following best summarizes the passage?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec1-VQ20', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (B). &nbsp;The passage discusses Venezuela under Chavez specifically, so it cannot be the basis for a general statement as presented in (A), which is far broader than the scope of the passage. &nbsp;There is no discussion of who is expected to address human rights abuses or the record of the women in power, so (C) is incorrect.  The passage does mention Chavez’s sexist rhetoric, but does not draw a correlation between this and his policy, so it cannot summarize the complete passage, eliminating (D). &nbsp;While there may be some truth to choice (E), it is not a statement that best summarizes the passage.  Choice (B) is correct because it highlights the progress and concerns expressed in the passage</span></p>', 1001),
(1382, 1, 687651, 'verbal', '', '<p>Samantha\'s parents and elementary school teachers noticed her ______________ talent for mathematics and encouraged her with challenging number puzzles.</p>', 3, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ01', '<p>Credited answers are developed and evolved\nCredited answer is precocious\nPrecocious means developing an ability or talent at an earlier than usual age.  Determined might describe Samantha, but it does not describe the talent as well.  Precocious is the right answer.</p>', 1001),
(1383, 1, 692272, 'verbal', '', '<p>The  &#34;______________ of the nursery&#34; was a phrase used to describe William Brighty Rands (1823-1882), who wrote prodigiously in children’s magazines and penned Lilliput Legends, Shoemaker\'s Village, and many other works.</p>', 3, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ02', '<p >Credited answer is laureate\nA laureate is someone honored for creative achievements, and is the best fit for the biographical sentence about William Rands.</p>', 1001),
(1384, 2, 858842, 'verbal', '', '<p>18th century changes in theological views were exhibited no less in (i) ______________.  Slegel explains that pastors began to counsel and encourage their flocks in the space of minutes where before, divines had (ii) ______________ and rebuked for hours.</p>', 3, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ03', '<p>Credited answers are homiletics and exhort\nHomiletics is the art of preaching a sermon, here described as a changing form.  To exhort is to strongly urge, a fitting companion to the older style and a contrast to the softer "counsel" of later times.</p>', 1001),
(1385, 3, 172335, 'verbal', '', '<p>Though the son of an attorney, and trained in the law himself, Edmund Burke preferred (i) ______________ to (ii) ______________.  His first work of note – a 1756 pamphlet -  turned Bolingbroke\'s own style and argumentation against itself.  Entitled, &#34;Vindication of Natural Society, by a late noble writer,&#34; it displayed Burke\'s (iii) ______________ and writing skill.</p>', 3, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ04', '<p>Credited answers are literature, jurisprudence and wit\nIn the first blank, "composing" is tempting, but it does not work grammatically.  Placing the noun "literature" in the first blank fits better with the noun that must go in the second blank.  One might have expected Burke to prefer jurisprudence, the theory of law, given his background.  A written work might reveal the malaise or ardor of an author, but here mental sharpness is displayed, so "wit" is the best fit. </p>', 1001),
(1386, 2, 638733, 'verbal', '', '<p>Her memories of tranquil childhood summers at the cape included walking along the (i) ______________, shady path, slowly strolling hand-in-hand with her mother.  They had a favorite (ii) ______________ on a dune nearby, from which they could view both forest and sea.</p>', 3, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ05', '<p >Credited answers are placid and prospect\nThe childhood memories are of peaceful and tranquil times; placid, therefore, best describes the path.  A prospect is a viewpoint.  An escarpment is a steep slope not likely to be found on or near a dune.</p>', 1001),
(1387, 3, 189618, 'verbal', '', '<p>Turpentine was for many years the only liquid used to thin paints.  Turpentine is made by (i) ______________ of the sap of the long-leaf pine, which is (ii) ______________ in the southeastern United States.  Now there are many (iii) ______________ for turpentine, including benzene.  </p>', 3, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ06', '<p>Credited answers are distilling, abundant and substitute\nDistilling is a process whereby a liquid is vaporized and condensed; it is the only choice here which explains the function of the pine sap.  The pine is plentiful, or abundant, in the Southeast, where turpentine is made.  Though there are various uses or applications for turpentine, but benzene is a substitute for it; turpentine is no longer the only liquid used to thin paints.</p>', 1001),
(1388, 0, 924238, 'verbal', '<p>The concept of “productive aging” has been used to promote older adults’ involvement in productive activities in their later years, regardless of whether these activities are compensated. Many public and private initiatives encourage older people to remain involved in productive activities, particularly formal volunteering. These initiatives frequently claim that formal volunteering not only provides a valuable service to the community, but also can actually improve the physical and mental health of older people.There has been a great deal of research that links formal volunteerism with increased physical and mental health of older people. Underlying much of the research on the connection between volunteerism and physical and mental health is the notion that being a volunteer is a productive role, which is an important role for people of all ages. Role theory suggests that through engaging in a productive role, such as being a volunteer, older people increase their social networks, resources and emotional gratification, all of which can have a positive effect on their physical and mental health.  Conversely, for those who volunteer too many hours, role theory suggests they may experience role strain and thus might not have any physical and mental health benefits from volunteering. Role theory is quite useful in explaining the mechanisms of why volunteerism could be linked with improved physical and mental health for older people.Most of the research on the correlation between volunteering and health, however, has measured health solely on the basis of an individual’s self-perceived health. Although perceptions of health themselves are important, as they often relate to an individual’s adaptations to a medical or mental condition, perceived health is not necessarily related to actual medical or mental conditions, or to physical or mental functioning, or to mortality. Changes in perceived health could signify that volunteering actually slows the onset of medical conditions and slows the decline in functioning of older people; or it could mean that volunteering simply changes people’s perceptions regarding their health or their adaptations to their health. Initiatives encouraging formal volunteering among older people should be careful not to promise improved physical and mental health.</p>', '<p>Which of the following statements could one infer from role theory as presented in this passage? </p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ07', '<p ><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (D). &nbsp;Answer choice (E) is tempting but incorrect. Role theory suggests that engaging in a productive role might lead to physical and mental health benefits, but does not suggest that people with declining physical and mental health would be more likely to seek out such a role. Choice (B) is not an inference that can be drawn from the passage. Choice (C) is incorrect, as role theory is not presented as suggesting that a productive role is more important for older as opposed to younger people. Finally, (A) is incorrect, as the first paragraph states that engaging in productive activities leads to benefits regardless of compensation. Thus, (D) is correct as a valid inference. People who overextend themselves might experience role strain.</span></p>', 1001),
