(1392, 0, 367415, 'verbal', '<p dir="ltr"><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The situation of Washington, at this moment, was extremely critical.  When he took possession of Trenton on the 29th of December, his force was only eighteen hundred continental troops; of these, twelve hundred were to be released on the first of January.  Attempts had been made, in vain, to detain them for a few weeks longer. A bounty of two dollars was offered for this period.  It was accepted, but nearly one half abandoned the camp immediately after.  At this time it was decided to advance the Pennsylvania militia to Washington\'s relief; but when they arrived, his total force of continentals and militia did not exceed five thousand.</span></p><p><br/></p><p dir="ltr"><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">To retreat with this force, at the very moment when the hearts of all America were lifted to exultation – to abandon a post with five thousand men, and retreat, immediately after having advanced and beaten the enemy with half that number, was but little else than quenching, at once, the light which had just been kindled.  Yet, to risk an action with a force so superior in front, and a river in the rear, was hazardous in the extreme.  The first might have eclipsed the star of their hopes for a time, but the latter, if the issue should be calamitous, would be blotting it out from the heavens.</span></p><!--EndFragment--><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', '<p>Based on information contained in the passage, which of the following best describes General Washington\'s dilemma in Trenton?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ10', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (C). &nbsp;Choices (A) and (B) are not supported by the text. &nbsp;Choice (D) focuses on his command, which is not described here as ever being in jeopardy. &nbsp;Choice (E) is close, as the flourished language seems to suggest it.  However, actual popular sentiment was not cited as being for or against retreat, leaving choice (C) as the best.</span></p>', 1001),
(1393, 0, 812860, 'verbal', '<p>The situation of Washington, at this moment, was extremely critical.  When he took possession of Trenton on the 29th of December, his force was only eighteen hundred continental troops; of these, twelve hundred were to be released on the first of January.  Attempts had been made, in vain, to detain them for a few weeks longer. A bounty of two dollars was offered for this period.  It was accepted, but nearly one half abandoned the camp immediately after.  At this time it was decided to advance the Pennsylvania militia to Washington\'s relief; but when they arrived, his total force of continentals and militia did not exceed five thousand.To retreat with this force, at the very moment when the hearts of all America were lifted to exultation – to abandon a post with five thousand men, and retreat, immediately after having advanced and beaten the enemy with half that number, was but little else than quenching, at once, the light which had just been kindled.  Yet, to risk an action with a force so superior in front, and a river in the rear, was hazardous in the extreme.  The first might have eclipsed the star of their hopes for a time, but the latter, if the issue should be calamitous, would be blotting it out from the heavens.</p>', '<p>In the context in which it appears, &#34;relief&#34; most nearly means</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ11', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  Consolation, solace, and even palliation speak to a person\'s emotional or physical relief, which is not the context of this passage.  At the time of the force\'s arrival, the army was not under attack, and therefore did not need deliverance.  Assistance is the best fit.</p>', 1001),
(1394, 0, 649356, 'verbal', '<p>The situation of Washington, at this moment, was extremely critical.  When he took possession of Trenton on the 29th of December, his force was only eighteen hundred continental troops; of these, twelve hundred were to be released on the first of January.  Attempts had been made, in vain, to detain them for a few weeks longer. A bounty of two dollars was offered for this period.  It was accepted, but nearly one half abandoned the camp immediately after.  At this time it was decided to advance the Pennsylvania militia to Washington\'s relief; but when they arrived, his total force of continentals and militia did not exceed five thousand.To retreat with this force, at the very moment when the hearts of all America were lifted to exultation – to abandon a post with five thousand men, and retreat, immediately after having advanced and beaten the enemy with half that number, was but little else than quenching, at once, the light which had just been kindled.  Yet, to risk an action with a force so superior in front, and a river in the rear, was hazardous in the extreme.  The first might have eclipsed the star of their hopes for a time, but the latter, if the issue should be calamitous, would be blotting it out from the heavens.</p>', '<p>The author of the passage employs poetic imagery primarily in order to</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ12', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  Choices (A) and (E) impute an unflattering agenda to the author, which is not supported by the passage.  The author would probably have described this event very differently, moreover, if his intentions were those in choices (C) and (D).  Choice (B) is the best option and keeps the focus on the moment. </p>', 1001),
(1395, 0, 470662, 'verbal', '<p>A major impediment to universal access to medication is the high cost of patented drugs, which are often specifically required by patients for survival.  In an attempt to make such drugs more widely available to patients, one drug company is planning to offer patients a free one-month drug supply for every $1,000 they spend on patented drugs.</p>', '<p>Which of the following, if true, most threatens the plan\'s prospects for success?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ13', '<p>The correct answer is (B). &nbsp;The plan seems to involve a large discount: one month of free drugs. &nbsp;The correct answer will probably show us that the deal isn’t quite as good as it sounds. If the overall price of a necessary medication plan remains the same in the long term, it will not make drugs more widely available, so Choice (B) is correct. Choice (A) would actually be helpful in reaching the goal of making drugs “more widely available to patients,” since the one-month free trial would often cover the entire necessary dose. &nbsp;&nbsp;Choice (C) suggests that the plan is irrelevant, if health insurance is paying the costs. Making the initial need for the plan unnecessary is not the same as threatening its success.   Choice (D) is also outside the scope of the passage — we are be concerned with the instances where generics are not available: “A major impediment to the universal access to medication is the high cost of patented drugs.”  Also, “whenever possible” is too vague; it could mean 10% or 90%. Choice (E) doesn’t threaten the plain; in fact, it seems to heighten its need, if patients must afford multiple patented drugs.</p>', 1001),
(1396, 0, 390564, 'verbal', '<p>Some experts warn that global warming will reduce food production.  Others are more hopeful, claiming that food production will change only minimally because there is little reason to expect altered rain distribution, even with warmer temperatures.  All agree that in the case of most crops, annual fluctuation in rainfall and increased use of agricultural technology mask the changes in yield that are due to temperature change.</p>', '<p>The claims of the more hopeful experts are based on which of the following assumptions?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ14', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  The experts in the second sentence are hopeful because they expect rainfall to continue undisturbed despite the temperature change.  That is, they are unconcerned about a warmer climate impacting food production because they believe that rainfall levels will remain the same and that rainfall is a more critical factor in food production than temperature.  Choice (D) is therefore the best alternative.  Choice (A) is incorrect, as the hopeful experts do not address technology in their reasoning.  While choice (B) might be true, it is irrelevant, as unpredictable climate change would give no one reason to be hopeful.  Choice (C) cannot be correct, as the hopeful experts base their hope on the predictability of rainfall trends; the passage does not comment on the predictability of temperature trends at all. This is also the reason choice (E) can be eliminated. </p>', 1001);
