(1397, 0, 954868, 'verbal', '<p>Golf in the United States is inherently a democratic sport.  Not only does it accommodate players of all ages, strengths, economic backgrounds and body types, but its professional ranks include a diverse mixture of people.</p>', '<p>Which of the following statements is LEAST effective in weakening the argument above?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ15', '<p>The correct answer is (E). This question asks you to find the answer choice that is least effective in weakening the argument.  Accordingly, the best plan of action is to go through the answer choices one by one, eliminating them if they weaken the argument.  Choice (A) weakens the conclusion by stating that golf is an elite sport, which runs counter to “democratic” ideals; a sport that is restricted to the wealthy flouts a majority of the population.  Choice (B) weakens the conclusion as well, as it suggests that golf equipment may not be available to everyone, making it not a truly democratic sport.  Choice (D) implies that access to courses is not egalitarian, which weakens the argument in a similar manner. Choice (C) weakens the argument by suggesting that despite golf\'s professional ranks including a “diverse mixture of people,” the sport may endorse some decidedly un-democratic institutions.  Choice (E) is the only answer choice that does not significantly weaken the argument.  The fact that golf is more egalitarian a sport in Scotland than it is in the United States would have no bearing on the strength of the argument. Even if golf is more egalitarian in Scotland, that doesn\'t mean it cannot be egalitarian or democratic in the United States.  Every answer choice except (E) presents information that weakens the argument in some manner. </p>', 1001),
(1398, 0, 525620, 'verbal', '<p>The administrators of a music downloading website were worried that the lack of downloadable movies and TV shows could diminish the popularity of their site.  Accordingly, they decided to survey their existing customers in order to determine whether adding movies would increase interest.  The survey found that only a small percentage of their current customers were interested in purchasing movies online, and the administrators concluded that adding movies would not significantly increase traffic to their site.</p>', '<p >Which of the following, if true, shows a flaw in the administrators’ reasoning?</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ16', '<p ><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (E). &nbsp;This question asks you to find a flaw in the administrators\' reasoning that leads them to conclude that adding movies wouldn\'t increase business for their site. This reasoning is based on the assumption that their survey correctly captures the opinions of all potential customers. Choice (E) shows that since the survey sample was skewed in favor of people whose main interest is music, the administrators were probably wrong to conclude that just because their existing customers don’t want to purchase movies, potential new customers won\'t either. This is called a biased sample error. You need to be careful here: a statement that just undermines the conclusion does not necessarily indicate a flaw in the administrators\' reasoning; the correct answer choice must address why the conclusion is inappropriately drawn from the evidence given. &nbsp;Choices (A) and (B) suggest that the conclusion was flawed; however, the information offered is irrelevant to a consideration of the administrators’ reasoning. Choices (C) and (D) likewise address irrelevant issues.</span></p>', 1001),
(1399, 0, 460187, 'verbal', '<p>For the classical scholar, the Germania by Tacitus is a minor work. However, for the student of the Germanic people, Tacitus’s ethnographic treatise is a major source of information, mainly reliable, about the German tribes of the first century A.D. Studies of Tacitus have often attempted to clarify the author’s purpose by defining it as an example of a particular literary genre. A few have seen the book primarily as a satire of Roman corruption, which uses the warlike but upright Germans as a stick with which to beat the degeneracy Tacitus observed in his contemporary Rome. Others classify the book as an extended political pamphlet whose central purpose is to urge Emperor Trajan to take some decisive Roman action to destroy the growing threat posed by the German tribes. Both of these themes are present in the Germania, but not central to its purpose; if they were, Tacitus would certainly have made them more prominent and explicit. The book’s purpose is obvious — to fully explain to a Roman audience what was known of the character of a neighboring people. In this task, Tacitus was following the examples of several earlier ethnographers, including Livy, whose books included an ethnographic study of the German people, and Seneca, who wrote works about the peoples of India and Egypt that resembled the Germania. Such works formed the type to which the Germania belongs, and though most of the examples are lost, it seems to have been a recognized genre of the period.However, as with most ethnographic studies, the Germania reveals as much about the preoccupations of the society to which its author belonged as about the people who are the work’s ostensible subject. Thus, the fear of a German threat to Rome is reflected in the military orientation of the study. The picture Tacitus paints is of a warlike people, a society that regards weapons as “the equivalent of the man’s toga with the Romans” and “the first distinction publicly conferred upon a youth, who now ceases to rank merely as a member of a household and becomes a citizen. The Germans even applaud in assembly, not by clapping, but by clashing their spears.”  If Tacitus’s aim was to arouse Romans’ concern over a German military threat, his choice of details surely advanced his purpose.</p>', '<p>The author’s primary purpose in the passage is to</p>', 4, 'Test1-Sec2-VQ17', '<p >The correct answer is (E).  The great bulk of the passage is devoted to showing that the Germania is not a satire or a political pamphlet but an ethnographic study focusing on aspects of German culture — namely its military aspects — that were of greatest concern to the Romans of the time. Hence, choice (E) is correct. The other answers choices all describe ideas secondary to the main purpose of the passage. </p>', 1001),
