he workforce in increasing numbers, the number of workers has increased. Similarly, the number of unemployed workers who are now eligible to collect benefits has increased. To the extent that these changes have increased voluntary and involuntary layoff rates and the average length of time unemployed persons spend looking for work, the full employment rate has risen.</p>', '<p>The passage provides information to answer which of the following?</p>', 4, 'Test3-Sec1-VQ18', '<p>The correct answer is (A). The question in Choice (A) is discussed in the first paragraph of the passage. The other questions may all be raised by the information provided in the passage, but none of them can be answered by the passage.</p>', 1001),
(1523, 0, 774298, 'Verbal', '<p>The full employment rate cannot be determined with great precision. One thing is certain: the unemployment rate cannot be zero or even close to zero. A zero unemployment rate would mean that no one ever entered or re-entered the labor force, that no one ever left a job and that the process of searching for a job consumed no time. Moreover, full  employment cannot be defined as an equality between the number of unemployed persons and the number of unfilled jobs. By this definition, almost any unemployment rate could be consistent with the full employment rate.In the U.S., the customary definition of the full employment rate is the lowest rate of unemployment that can be attained without resulting in an accelerated rate of inflation, given the existing economic conditions. However, based on this definition, no one can be sure exactly what the full employment rate is since it is impossible to predict exactly how much change in the rate of inflation will be associated with any given change in the unemployment rate. In the early 1960s, President Kennedy\'s Council of Economic Advisors (CEA) determined that 4 percent was the best estimate of the full employment rate. That rate was based on data collected during the period from mid-1955 to mid-1957, when the unemployment rate fluctuated around an average of 4.1 percent and the consumer price index advanced at an average rate of 2.5 percent per year. Although a 4 percent unemployment rate may have been consistent with an acceptably low rate of inflation in the mid-1950s, by the 1960s this proposition had become increasingly questionable. Our experience since then has been such that those who accept the customary definition of the full employment rate now consider 4.5 percent to be the optimal rate under the existing circumstances. The principal reason for this upward adjustment in the full employment rate is the changed composition of the labor force. As elderly people and women have joined the workforce in increasing numbers, the number of workers has increased. Similarly, the number of unemployed workers who are now eligible to collect benefits has increased. To the extent that these changes have increased voluntary and involuntary layoff rates and the average length of time unemployed persons spend looking for work, the full employment rate has risen.</p>', '<p>The purpose of the third paragraph is to </p>', 4, 'Test3-Sec1-VQ19', '<p>The correct answer is (C). The second paragraph presents the issue of adjusting the full employment rate over the years, but it is not until paragraph three that we understand why this was necessary: the composition of the labor force had changed. Therefore, the purpose of paragraph three is to explain a statement made in paragraph two.</p>', 1001),
(1524, 0, 413116, 'Verbal', '<p>Which of the following statements is true, according to the passage?</p>', '<p>John Baker’s 2011 triumph at Alaska’s Iditarod dog-sled race provides the first native Alaskan victory in over thirty years;  Baker is further distinguished by his Eskimo heritage, making his an unprecedented accomplishment within that culture.Which of the following statements is true, according to the passage?</p>', 4, 'Test3-Sec1-VQ20', '<p>The correct answer is (C). &nbsp;The sentence states that Baker is the first native Alaskan in thirty years, indicating that Alaskans have won before, thus eliminating (A). &nbsp;Since he is the first Eskimo to win the race, the sentence does not indicate that Eskimos are distinguished in the sport, making (B) incorrect. &nbsp;The fact that an Eskimo has not won this race does not mean that, as a group, they do not receive accolades in other areas, so (D) is incorrect.  While Choice (E) might be true, there is no evidence in the passage to support this conclusion. &nbsp;Because Baker’s victory is unprecedented for Eskimos, he must be the first to have won, so (C) is correct.</p>', 1001),
(1525, 1, 819667, 'Verbal', '', '<p>The walls of plant cells are made of a structural material called cellulose; it makes up a third of dried vegetable matter.  Cellulose is _______________, being called &#34;the commonest of common things&#34; and forming the basis of thousands of products.</p>', 3, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ1', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Your Choice: ubiquitous</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited Answer: ubiquitous</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">As cellulose is in plant cells and is very common, it is likely to be found everywhere, which is the meaning of ubiquitous</span></p>', 1001),
(1526, 0, 724968, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Catiline, the famous Roman politician, was known for his many conspiracies to attain power.  Though frequently making beguiling promises to other patricians or the citizenry, his ______________ proved his undoing, and he was driven from Rome and then killed in battle.</p>', 2, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ2', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Your Choice: avarice</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited Answer: machinations</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">A machination is a plot or scheme, which Catiline engaged in continually. Note that avarice (greed), while a tempting choice, is incorrect. &nbsp;Catiline thirsted after power, not money.</span></p>', 1001),
(1527, 2, 563872, 'Verbal', '', '<p>The fiery eloquence of Daniel O\'Connell established his reputation as a brilliant (i)_______________ . His actions led to the 1829 (ii)________________ of the oath which had previously prevented Catholics such as him from taking a seat in Parliament.</p>', 3, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ3', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited Answer(s):</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(i) orator</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(ii) abolishment</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">An orator is one who displays brilliant speech. &nbsp;Since after 1829 the oath was no longer in effect it must have been eliminated, or abolished.</span></p>', 1001),
(1528, 3, 964848, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Some trade associations are seeking to (i)_____________ the defection of members by issuing dire warnings about the consequences of a weakened representative body.  Some are taking a more (ii)________________ approach and lowering annual membership dues.  Still others are hoping to retain members by (iii)_________________ with other organizations, thus increasing their relevance and reach.</p>', 3, 'Test2-Sec1-VQ6', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited Answers:</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(i) &nbsp;deter</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(ii) &nbsp;pecuniary</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(iii) &nbsp;affiliating</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The subject concerns losses in membership and in particular how associations would like to prevent, or deter, them from happening. &nbsp;Some use financial, or pecuniary, incentives.  Others link, or affiliate, with different organizations.</span></p>', 1001),
(1529, 3, 866968, 'Verbal', '', '<p>The United States War Department (i)_____________ chewing gum as part of soldiers’ rations in World War II.  This was because chewing gum was considered a harmless way to (ii)______________ stress and increase concentration.  Thus it was that American war planning (iii)________________ popularized chewing gum in Europe.</p>', 3, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ4', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited Answer(s):</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(i) issued</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(ii) relieve</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(iii) inadvertently</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Issued correctly describes how chewing gum was distributed as part of the rations. To contrive is to bring about using skill and artifice, while banned does not make sense. &nbsp;Gum was issued to take away, or relieve stress.  The intention was to help soldiers, not market a confection, so its popularization on was inadvertent, or not planned.</span></p>', 1001),
(1530, 2, 241583, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Last week, Gilman Norris, spokesman of the Allocation Board, issued a (i)______________ of a previous statement that had withdrawn support for the Manasseh Project.  The Project will continue, as previously planned.  No explanation was given for the (ii)_________________.  </p>', 3, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ5', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited Answer(s):(i) retraction &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(ii) reversal</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The Allocation Board first issued a statement withdrawing support from the project, then changed its mind and had to issue a retraction, or draw back what it had previously said. &nbsp;It did so without explaining the change, or reversal.</span></p>', 1001),
(1531, 3, 731080, 'Verbal', '', '<p>It was Charles Dickens, over 150 years ago, who best described a citizen\'s (i)_____________ when at the mercy of an impenetrable government bureaucracy.  His character in Little Dorritt encounters the &#34;Office of (ii)________________&#34; which, as its name implies, deliberately (iii)__________ the resolution of matters through endless requirements and complications. </p>', 3, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ6', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Credited Answer(s):</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(i) exasperation</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(ii) Circumlocution</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">(iii) impedes</span></p> <p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Exasperation is great irritation, which citizens would experience if dealing with an impenetrable bureaucracy. &nbsp;The Office of Circumlocution is a classic image of government existing for itself: forms are required in order to fill out other forms. &nbsp;These clerical requirements create a barrier to getting things done; they effectively impede the resolution of matters.</span></p>', 1001),
(1532, 0, 315307, 'Verbal', '<p>While the heroic life might well win practical success for a king, it also had another, perhaps more important, end – enduring fame.  In cultures whose religion, unlike Christianity, offers no firm promise of rewards in an afterlife, a name that will live on after one’s death serves as the closest substitute for immortality.  Thus arises the heroic paradox, still latent in our own civilization, that by dying gloriously one may achieve immortality.</p>', '<p>Which word or phrase most closely mirrors the concept of the “heroic life?”</p>', 4, 'Test2-Sec1-VQ7', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (B). Deferred gratification most closely mirrors the concept of the “heroic life,” in that one forgoes something now in order to have a reward in the future. This accurately describes the glorious death (giving up life) in order to achieve fame (immortality) that is the heroic life. &nbsp;&nbsp;Choice (A), parthenogenesis, is asexual reproduction;  Choice (C), opportunity cost, describes the options that are forgone when a particular action or investment is chosen. Choice (D), random walk, says that you can’t predict future actions by what has occurred in the past. And Choice (E), chance encounter, has nothing to do with the death/immortality theme of the heroic life.</span></p>', 1001),
(1533, 0, 754979, 'Verbal', '<p>The news of 2003 is that Japan is making a comeback. After 15 years in a weak state, its economy is finally beginning to show signs of life. Deflation is over; prices are no longer falling. Japan has the second largest economy in the world and its recent growth is very good news. Manufacturers in the rest of Asia and America will undoubtedly benefit. American consumers had been carrying the majority of the responsibility for keeping the global economy moving. Now Japan appears to be engaging in real consumption, an indicator that renewal is upon the Japanese economy. Japan’s economy barely grew at all in the 1990s. Deflation plagued the country for years. It reduced wages, prices and corporate income and made debt all the more heavy. Real estate values fell for 14 years in a row, amounting to a decline of about 60 percent over that time. The Nikkei index of stock prices fell from an all-time high of 39,000 to below 8,000 before climbing back to about 17,000. It was a bizarre time. Japan lowered interest rates again and again until they hit zero in 2001. Bond prices fell so low that even 30-year government bonds yielded less than one percent. Economic historians were known for saying that the cost of borrowing money had never been so low — not in the financial transactions of ancient Greece, Rome, China, or anywhere else in recorded history. Even so, zero percent interest rates continued. Only now are Japan’s bankers talking about the possibility of lifting rates by a quarter of a percent in the coming months. This month, Japan’s central bank finally put a stop to “quantitative easing,” a 50-year-old policy of pushing excess money into the financial system. Japan was able to do so because consumer prices have recently begun to rise, slowly but surely. Japan’s population is aging and its public debt will continue to trouble the country in the long term. But, in the short term, American politicians will almost certainly once again begin fussing about the miracle of the Japanese, and resume complaining about Japan grabbing up U.S. properties.</p>', '<p>I. has ended the zero percent interest rate.II. used to have a lauded economy III. has higher inflation than it has had for years</p>', 4, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ7', '<p><span id="docs-internal-guid-d81f6155-5af7-2e13-6f2a-7d41d831a364"><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (D). &nbsp;In the fifth paragraph, the passage states that Japan’s consumer prices have finally begun to rise, “slowly but surely,” indicating that it is now suffering inflation. Given that until recently consumer prices had fallen for many years – deflation – it follows that its current inflation is worse than it has been for a long time, so III is correct. The sixth paragraph mentions, in the context of the Japanese economy, that Americans will soon again be talking about “the miracle of the Japanese,” implying that Japan’s economy was in the past thought of as miraculous, so II is correct. But the fourth paragraph mentions that only now are Japan’s bankers “talking about” raising the interest rate by a small amount above the long-standing zero rate “in the coming months” – it has not yet happened in the present of the passage. So I is incorrect. That makes (D) the correct answer choice.</span></span></p>', 1001);
