fussing about the miracle of the Japanese, and resume complaining about Japan grabbing up U.S. properties.</p>', '<p>The author believes that Japan’s current financial state is </p>', 4, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ9', '<p>The correct answer is (C). &nbsp;At the very outset of the passage, we are told that “Japan is making a comeback. After 15 years in a weak state, its economy is finally beginning to show signs of life.” The author characterizes these developments as “good news.” This indicates that the author’s attitude toward the Japanese economy is one of cautious hope. Choices (B) and (E) are too extreme for the cautious optimism the author exhibits, and (A) and (D) are incorrect because they give negative views.</p>', 1001),
(1536, 0, 446726, 'Verbal', '<p>During Reconstruction, many Southern planters, accustomed to absolute control over their labor force, sought a new system that was slavery in all but name. Former slaves opposed this. After years of providing uncompensated labor they felt entitled to land; “forty acres and a mule” became their rallying cry.White reluctance to sell to blacks, as well as the federal government\'s decision not to redistribute land in the South, meant that only a small percentage of former slaves became landowners. Instead, most former slaves rented land or worked for wages on plantations. Meanwhile, the war had forced some small, white-owned farms into poverty, and during Reconstruction, many of these properties were converted from a subsistence-crop (food grown for the family) to a cotton crop.  Shaped by these conflicts, new systems of labor emerged. Sharecropping came to dominate the cotton and tobacco fields and wage labor was the rule on the sugar plantations.What had changed drastically was that rural blacks now had control over their lives. Rather than continue with field labor, many black women devoted more time to their families. Children, whose labor had been dictated by plantation owners under slavery, now attended school. As a result, plantation owners complained of a persistent “labor shortage” throughout Reconstruction.</p>', '<p>According to the author, which of the following was true of the Reconstruction-era sharecropping system?</p>', 4, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ10', '<p>The correct answer is (D). The end of paragraph one states that cotton and tobacco employed sharecroppers. &nbsp;Choice (A) is wrong since sharecropping was practiced by blacks.  (B) is also backwards, as it was more prevalent on cotton and tobacco plantations. &nbsp;(C) is not supported by the passage; we only know that some whites “sought a system that was slavery in all but name” — not that they achieved it.  Finally, (E) characterizes the state of small white farmers before the war, not sharecroppers after the war.</p>', 1001),
