(1538, 0, 170071, 'Verbal', '<p>During Reconstruction, many Southern planters, accustomed to absolute control over their labor force, sought a new system that was slavery in all but name. Former slaves opposed this. After years of providing uncompensated labor they felt entitled to land; “forty acres and a mule” became their rallying cry.White reluctance to sell to blacks, as well as the federal government\'s decision not to redistribute land in the South, meant that only a small percentage of former slaves became landowners. Instead, most former slaves rented land or worked for wages on plantations. Meanwhile, the war had forced some small, white-owned farms into poverty, and during Reconstruction, many of these properties were converted from a subsistence-crop (food grown for the family) to a cotton crop.  Shaped by these conflicts, new systems of labor emerged. Sharecropping came to dominate the cotton and tobacco fields and wage labor was the rule on the sugar plantations.What had changed drastically was that rural blacks now had control over their lives. Rather than continue with field labor, many black women devoted more time to their families. Children, whose labor had been dictated by plantation owners under slavery, now attended school. As a result, plantation owners complained of a persistent “labor shortage” throughout Reconstruction.</p>', '<p>The passage is primarily concerned with</p>', 4, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ12', '<p>The correct answer is (B). Since We can scan the opening verbs in the five choices and narrow our options. &nbsp;The passage is not “correcting” anything(D), nor does it “reassert” anything (E).  That leaves the first three choices. &nbsp;Choice (A) is far too limited, since very little of the passage specifically deals with the role of black women.  Choice (C) is similarly narrow. &nbsp;The passage does mention these complaints, but it is a single detail in a three-paragraph passage.  (B) is correct. The author spends the entire passage detailing the effects of Reconstruction on sharecroppers and former slaves.</p>', 1001),
(1540, 0, 346924, 'Verbal', '<p>Although most people in the modern world believe that it is necessary to shower daily, the human body will actually regulate its production of excessive oils if left unwashed.  Thus, contrary to popular belief, showering daily causes you to smell worse than you would otherwise. </p>', '<p>The argument  assumes that </p>', 4, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ14', '<p>The correct answer is (B). This is an assumption question. &nbsp;The argument claims that because the human body will regulate its production of oils if left unwashed, it is unnecessary to shower daily and, furthermore, showering daily will actually cause you to smell worse than you would if you did not shower every day. &nbsp;&nbsp;To find the assumption in the argument, look for the answer choice that must be true for the argument to be valid.  Choice (B) is the only choice that must be true: if it is not the case that the odor of the human body is caused by the oils it produces, then the argument makes no sense, since it assumes a causal link between oils and the body’s odor. &nbsp;Choice (A) contains unrelated information; the argument says nothing about deodorants, so this needn’t be true for the argument to be valid.  Choice (C) is not an assumption on which the argument depends because the argument only assumes that people now believe that it is necessary to shower daily; the argument could still be true even if people in the ancient world also believed that it was necessary to shower daily. &nbsp;Choice (D) is too strong; the argument merely says that not showering helps to regulate the body’s production of oils, not that showering halts the body’s production of oils entirely.  Choice (E) is an unfounded conclusion.  (B) is the best answer.</p>', 1001),
(1541, 0, 905807, 'Verbal', '<p>The English spoken across the Atlantic began to receive admiring commentaries from British visitors. William Eddis, who toured the colonies in 1770, was surprised to find that “the language of the immediate descendants of such a promiscuous ancestry is perfectly uniform and unadulterated; nor has it borrowed any provincial, or national accent, from its British or foreign parentage.”A few years later, another visitor noted: “It is a curious fact that there is perhaps no one portion of the British empire in which two or three million people speak their mother-tongue with greater purity, or a truer pronunciation, than the white inhabitants of the United States.” Even John Witherspoon noted that “the vulgar in America speak much better than the vulgar in England.”L. Dillard has suggested that the colonists created a koine language, a kind of standardized dialect that often emerges among a group of emigrants speaking various dialects of one basic language. When the colonists came to North America, they left behind their old social order, including the social rankings of dialects. They came in contact with a wide range of other languages: the foreign tongues of the maritime trade, the Creoles of slaves, the languages of the Indians. These influences accelerated the breakdown of the colonists’ English regional dialects and resulted in the formation of a naturally standardized American speech pattern, which British visitors later discovered and praised.English opinions of American speech, of course, were of little interest to the colonists, who quite impolitely proceeded to separate themselves from the empire. In the aftermath of the Revolution, there was understandably even less of an urge to subscribe to English authority, in matters of language or anything else and the Americans embarked on a period of furious growth and industry with occasional romanticism.</p>', '<p>The author would agree with which of the following statements?</p>', 4, 'Test2-Sec1-VQ8', '<p>The correct answer is (E), the only statement that is backed up by evidence in the passage.  The author refers to Dillard’s view that “influences accelerated the breakdown of the colonists’ English regional dialects and resulted in the formation of a naturally standardized American speech pattern.” Choice (A) is not substantiated by the passage. The author tells us that Americans didn’t care what the English thought of their speech, so this could not have been used against the English. Choice (B) ties the vulgarity mentioned in paragraph two with the language standardization mentioned in paragraph three. Choice (C) is not substantiated by evidence in the passage. The last line of the passage tells us America prospered but attributes it to a lack of British authority. Choice (D) is not supported by the passage – in fact, the very opposite of (D) appears to be true: in paragraph two, Witherspoon tells us that the English don’t speak as well as the Americans and that the vulgarities of the former are worse than those of the latter. </p>', 1001),
(1542, 0, 172545, 'Verbal', '<p>Since the arrival of the new convenience store near the school, fewer students are drinking the free apple juice that is provided to them by the school. This seems to be the result of the convenience store’s sales campaign directed toward students that offers soft drinks to the students at half-price before 9 am. Although there is a difference in nutritional value between the soft drinks and the free apple juice, many students have been seen drinking soft drinks outside the convenience store each morning before school and declining the apple juice in the cafeteria.</p>', '<p>What is the main point made in the passage? </p>', 4, 'Test3-Sec2-VQ15', '<p>The correct answer is (A). &nbsp;Notice that the passage never takes a stand on whether or not apple juice is healthier than are soft drinks – it does not constitute an argument. Rather, it merely makes a passive observation about the drinking habits of students in the morning, so (A) is correct. Answers (B) and (C) give opinions that are probably good opinions, but that simply aren’t found in the passage. The passage does not actually go as far as to make the statement contained in choice (D) — it refers to a difference in nutritional values, but does not explicitly state which drink is the more nutritious or suggest the difference is “much higher.” Choice (E) is not relevant. Choice (A) is the best answer.</p>', 1001),
