(1590, 0, 373869, 'Verbal', '<p>Although most people in the modern world believe that it is necessary to shower daily, the human body will actually regulate its production of excessive oils if left unwashed.  Thus, contrary to popular belief, showering daily causes you to smell worse than you would otherwise. </p>', '<p>The argument  assumes that </p>', 4, 'Test3_sec2-VQ13', '<p><span id="docs-internal-guid-335552f8-5aff-85da-78cd-ea766fa9555b"><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">The correct answer is (B). This is an assumption question. &nbsp;The argument claims that because the human body will regulate its production of oils if left unwashed, it is unnecessary to shower daily and, furthermore, showering daily will actually cause you to smell worse than you would if you did not shower every day. &nbsp;&nbsp;To find the assumption in the argument, look for the answer choice that must be true for the argument to be valid.  Choice (B) is the only choice that must be true: if it is not the case that the odor of the human body is caused by the oils it produces, then the argument makes no sense, since it assumes a causal link between oils and the body’s odor. &nbsp;Choice (A) contains unrelated information; the argument says nothing about deodorants, so this needn’t be true for the argument to be valid.  Choice (C) is not an assumption on which the argument depends because the argument only assumes that people now believe that it is necessary to shower daily; the argument could still be true even if people in the ancient world also believed that it was necessary to shower daily. &nbsp;Choice (D) is too strong; the argument merely says that not showering helps to regulate the body’s production of oils, not that showering halts the body’s production of oils entirely.  Choice (E) is an unfounded conclusion.  (B) is the best answer.</span></span></p>', 1001),
(1594, 0, 752283, 'Quant', '', '<p>As shown in the figure above, two sides of the triangle BCD are each 9 feet long.  The triangle BCD shares the side BD with the square ABDE, and the angle CBD measures 45°.  What is the total area of the figure ABCDE in square feet? (Note: The figure is not drawn to scale.)</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1530594919.jpg"/></p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q1', '<p>The correct answer is (C). Since the triangle BCD is an isosceles triangle, and we know that the angle CBD measures 45°, we also know that the angle CDB measures 45° (since these are the two angles opposite to the sides of equal length).Since all the angles in a triangle must add up to 180°, we know that the angle BCD is a right angle.  Thus, the triangle is an isosceles right triangle, and its sides are proportional to each other in the ratio of 1 : 1 : ?2. Since each of the legs of the triangle measures 9 feet, the hypotenuse measures 9?2 feet. The length of the hypotenuse of the triangle is also the length of each side of the square.  The base and height of the triangle are the legs, both measuring 9 feet.  We now have enough information to calculate the area of the figure.To determine the area of the square portion, we square the length of one side of the square:The area of the square = 9?2² = 9 × ?2 × 9 × ?2= 9 × 9 × ?2 × ?2 = 81 × 2 = 162.We can determine the area of the triangular portion since the base and height are 9 (the hypotenuse is 9?2) using the formula for the area of triangles:The area of the triangle = (1/2)(b × h)= (1/2)(9 × 9)= (1/2)(81) = 40.5.The area of the entire figure is therefore:40.5 + 162 = 202.5 square feet.The correct answer is C.</p>', 1001),
(1595, 0, 194086, 'Quant', '', '<p>   Quantity A:                                       Quantity B:The slope of a line                        The slope of the line perpendicular to y = 5x + 6          -2x + 10y = 10</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q2', '<p>The correct answer is (B). The slope of a line in the form y = 5x + 6 is the coefficient of x, or 5.   A line perpendicular to y = 5x + 6 will have a slope that is the negative reciprocal of the original slope, or -1/5.  The slope of a line in the form Ax + By = C is -A/B.  So the slope of -2x + 10y = 10 is -(-2)/10 = 1/5.  1/5 is greater than -1/5.  Quantity B is greater.</p>', 1001),
(1596, 0, 923283, 'Quant', '', '<p>The chart above shows the distribution of letter grades for three groups of students on one test. The vertical axis shows numbers of students. Point values are assigned to the letter grades so that A = 4 points, B = 3 points, C = 2 points, and D = 1 point.  Which of the following values is the closest to the average (arithmetic mean) grade of students in the group 3?</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1530594946.jpg"/></p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q3', '<p>The correct answer is (B). There are 4 + 7 + 9 + 2 = 22 students in the group 3.The grade distribution in the group 3 was:4 students received D.7 students received C.9 students received B.2 students received A.Therefore, the sum of the grade points for the group 3 is:(4 × 1) + (7 × 2) + (9 × 3) + (2 × 4) =4 + 14 + 27 + 8 = 53.We can find the average grade in the group 3 by dividing this sum by the number of students in the group 3:The average = 53/22.Performing the required division, we see that 2.4 is the closest answer choice.The correct answer is B.</p>', 1001),
(1597, 0, 492691, 'Quant', '', '<p>If in the figure above the semicircles X and Y have radii of 6 and 8 feet respectively, then what is the area of the semicircle Z (in square feet)? (Note: The figure is not drawn to scale.)</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1530594977.jpg"/></p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q4', '<p>The correct answer is (D). If the radii of the semicircles X and Y are 6 feet and 8 feet, then their diameters are 12 and 16 feet.  These diameters are both the lengths of the legs of the right triangle, and the diameter of semicircle Z is the hypotenuse of this triangle.The triangle is a 3-4-5 triangle, since the perpendicular legs are in the ratio 3 : 4.  So the hypotenuse measures 20 feet, meaning the diameter of Z is 20 feet and its radius is 10 feet.To determine the area of semicircle Z, we will determine the area of a full circle with the same radius as Z, and then divide this quantity by 2.The area of a circle with the radius 10 is:The area = ?r²   The area = ?10² = 100?.Thus, the area of the semicircle Z is 50? square feet. The correct answer is D.</p>', 1001),
(1598, 0, 102317, 'Quant', '', '<p>21w = 28z<br>\nQuantity A: 3w<br>\nQuantity B: 4z<br></p>\n\n\n', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q5', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  In order to compare the two values, we need to simplify the original expression first. If we divide the both sides of the given equality 21w = 28z by 7, we get 3w = 4z. These are the same values we are being asked to compare! Since we are told that they are equal, we must choose the choice C.</p>', 1001),
(1599, 0, 216123, 'Quant', '', '<p>Quantity A: 3 + 4 – 5 – 8<br>\nQuantity B: 12 – 6 + 1 – 3</p>\n', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q6', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  Evaluate from left to right.Quantity A:  3 + 4 – 5 – 8 = 7 – 5 – 8 = 2 – 8 = -6.Quantity B: (12 – 6 + 1 – 3) = (6 + 1 – 3) = (7 – 3) = 4.4 is greater than -6.  Quantity B is greater.</p>', 1001),
(1600, 0, 816136, 'Quant', '', 'x and y are positive integers, and x &lt; y .Quantity A:                        Quantity B:      x/y                                     ?(x/y)', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q7', '<p>x/y ?? ?(x/y)    (?(x/y))² ?? ?(x/y)Divide both sides by ?(x/y), which is positive so the sign will NOT change.?(x/y) ?? 1Multiply by ?y. It is positive, so the sign will NOT change.  ?x &lt; ?y because we know that x &lt; y.</p>', 1001),
(1601, 0, 769843, 'Quant', '', '<p>Quantity A: x + y<br>\nQuantity B: 90<br>\n</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q8', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  Since there are 180 degrees in a triangle, x + y + z = 180.  Since z is a right angle, it has 90 degrees.  By substitution, then, we get x + y + 90 = 180, and so x + y = 90.  The quantities A and B are equal.</p>', 1001),
(1602, 0, 188503, 'Quant', '', '<p>A company needs to paint all surfaces of a closed cylindrical can which is 100 cm tall.  The radius of the circular top is 10 cm.  How many square centimeters will need to be painted?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q9', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  Let\'s break down the can into three parts:  the circular top, the circular bottom, and the vertical part (similar to where the label of a soup can would go around the can).The area of the top and the bottom is found by using A = ?r², which becomes A = ?(10)², or 100? for the top and also 100? for the bottom, for a total of 200 ? square cm.Now let\'s find the &#34;soup can label&#34; area.  Think of taking the label off the soup can and laying it out flat.  It will be a rectangle, with height 100 cm and length equal to the circumference of the circle (because it was wrapped around the outside of the circular top and bottom).  The circumference of the circle, using C = 2?r, is equal to 2?(10), which becomes 20?.  Now we have the dimensions of the soup can label: (20? cm) long and (100 cm) high, so the &#34;label&#34; part of the cylinder is A = (20?)(100), or 2000?.Let\'s put this all together:  Add the top, the bottom, and the &#34;label&#34; part of the cylinder to get the total surface area:  (100?) + (100?) + (2000 ?) = 2,200 ?.  The correct answer</p>', 1001),
(1603, 0, 402782, 'Quant', '', '<p>An admissions panel is to be formed, consisting of 3 administrators and 4 faculty members.  If there are 5 administrators and 7 faculty members who are eligible to serve on the admissions panel, in how many possible ways can the selection be made?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q10', '<p>The correct answer is (C). You must first find how many ways to choose 3 administrators out of 5;  this is the number of combinations of 5 things taken 3 at a time which is calculated as:  5!/(3! × 2!) = (5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1)/(3 × 2 × 1 × 2 × 1) = 10.  Secondly, calculate how many ways in which you can choose 4 faculty members from a pool of 7:  7!/(4! × 3!) = (7 × 6 × 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1)/(4 × 3 × 2 × 1 × 3 × 2 × 1) = 35.Now, each of the 10 administrator possibilities  can be matched with each of the 35 faculty member possibilities, yielding 10 × 35 = 350 different ways of getting an admissions panel consisting of 3 administrators and 4 faculty members. The correct answer is C.</p>', 1001),
(1604, 0, 684405, 'Quant', '', '<p>What is the sum of the distinct prime factors of 693?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q11', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  We must perform the prime factorization of 693, but with such a large number, it may be little tricky to find factors.  Applying divisibility rules is a good way to start.Recall the mathematical rule that if the sum of the digits of a number is divisible by three, the number itself is divisible by three. Let’s divide 693 by 3 to start:693/3 = 231.We can again divide by 3, getting 231 = 3 × 77.  It is easy to see that 77 = 7 × 11. Now let\'s collect all the prime factors of 693:  (3)(3)(7)(11). The question asks for the sum of the distinct prime factors, not the sum of all of the prime factors. The sum we are looking for is: 3 + 7 + 11 = 21.  The correct answer is D.</p>', 1001),
(1605, 0, 987533, 'Quant', '', '<p>Assume that births of babies born at a hospital are independent events, with the probability of a girl = 0.5 and the probability of a boy = 0.5 .  What is the probability that of the next 3 babies born at the hospital, two of them are girls and one is a boy? (Note:  the two girl and one boy babies can be born in any order.) Express your answer as a decimal value, rounded to three decimal places.</p>', 5, 'Test4-Sec1-Q12', '<p>The correct answer is 0.375 .  There are 8 different ways in which 3 babies can be born:  GGG, GGB, GBG, BGG, BBG, BGB, GBB, and BBB. The probability of each of these eight ways is (.5)(.5)(.5) = .125.  Notice that exactly three of the eight ways (GGB, GBG, and BGG) satisfy the requirement that two girls and one boy were born.  Add these three probabilities together to get .375.</p>', 1001),
(1606, 0, 486697, 'Quant', '', '<p>How many more degrees of arc are there in 1/4 of a circle than in 1/5 of a circle?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q13', '<p>The correct answer is (B). A circle has 360 degrees.  1/4  of a circle has 90 degrees, and 1/5 of a circle has 72 degrees.  Their difference is 90 – 72 = 18, the choice (B).</p>', 1001),
(1607, 0, 949950, 'Quant', '', '<p>The chart shows the distribution by age of the incoming students at H. Parker Community College. At new student orientation, students will be divided into groups.  If students are divided into groups of 15, what fraction of all the students will be left over without a complete group?</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1530594997.jpg"/><br/></p>', 5, 'TEst4-Sec1-Q14', '<p>The correct answer is 7/547. To begin, find the total number of students.  246 + 167 + 65 + 42 + 27 = 547.  Then, divide 547 by 15 and find the remainder.  547/15 = 36 with a remainder of 7. There will be 36 complete groups of 15, and there will be 7 students, out of the total group of 547, that will be left over without a complete group.</p>', 1001),
(1608, 0, 937726, 'Quant', '', '<p>The chart shows the distribution by age of the incoming students at H. Parker Community College. Three students are selected at random, one at a time, to form a committee.  What is the probability that all three students selected are over 40 years old? (Round to thousandths of a percent).</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1530595016.jpg"/><br/></p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q15', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  First, find the total number of students.  (246 + 167 + 65 + 42 + 27) = 547.  Then, find the number of students over 40.  42 + 27 = 69 .The probability of selecting the first  student that is over 40 is 69/547.  Since one student has already been selected, there are only 546 remaining in the selection pool, and of those, there are now 68 who are over 40 years old, so this second probability is 68/546.  Finally, the third member is chosen out of the remaining 545 students, and he/she is one of 67 students over 40, and the probability is 67/545.  Multiply these probabilities together, since you want all the three occurrences to happen, and you will get (69/547)(68/546)(67/545) = 0.001931…, which rounds to 0.193%, choice (A).</p>', 1001),
(1609, 0, 368777, 'Quant', '', '<p>What is the angle between the hands of the clock when it is 4:40?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q16', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  A circle has 360 degrees, so each of the 12 sections of a standard 12-hour clock will have 360/12 = 30 degrees.  If the hour hand stayed stationary, at 4:40, the hour hand would be at 4 and the minute hand would be at 8, and the angle between them would be 120 degrees.  But the hour hand is not at 4;  it is somewhere between 4 and 5, and it is 40/60 of the way between 4 and 5, because at 4:40, exactly 40 minutes of the 60-minute hour have gone by.  Thus, the hour hand is 40/60 or 2/3 of the way between the 4 and 5, which in degrees is (2/3) × 30 = 20 degrees.  This means that the hour hand is 20 degrees closer to the 8 than earlier calculated, and thus the correct answer is (120 – 20) = 100 degrees, choice C.</p>', 1001),
(1610, 0, 593230, 'Quant', '', '<p>Larry can hoe a garden plot in 90 minutes, and Joe can hoe it in 60 minutes.  How long will it take them to hoe a garden plot if they work together?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q17', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  The key to this problem is to determine how much of the job each man can do per minute.  For Larry the rate per minute is 1/90.  For Joe it is 1/60.Now add the two rates together (since the two men are working together), and their sum is what part of the entire job they can accomplish, working together, in one minute.  Algebraically this becomes 1/90 + 1/60 = 2/180 + 3/180 = 5/180 = 1/36.Together they do 1/36 of the job in a minute, so it will take them 36 minutes to do the full job. The correct answer is C.</p>', 1001),
(1611, 0, 356747, 'Quant', '', '<p>If x is a positive integer and 2x² + 10x – 48 = 0, what is x?</p>', 5, 'Test4-Sec1-Q18', '<p>The correct answer is 3.  First, divide the entire equation by 2, resulting in x² + 5x – 24 = 0.  The resulting equation factors to (x + 8)(x – 3) = 0  (Or you can solve it using the regular formula for finding solutions).  x is either -8 or +3.  Since x is positive, x must equal 3</p>', 1001),
(1612, 0, 363770, 'Quant', '', '<p>Concentration of cleaning fluid must never exceed 15% when mixed with water. From the choices below, which amounts of water could be added to 3 gallons of cleaning fluid to result in an acceptable mixture?  </p>', 2, 'Test4-Sec1-Q19', '<p>The correct answers are 17 gallons and 20 gallons.  Let x be the amount of water that will be mixed with the 3 gallons of cleaning fluid.  The mixture now has (x + 3) gallons.  Since 15% of the mixture is the 3 gallons of cleaning fluid, we can say, then, that .15(x + 3)= 3. This equation becomes .15x + .45 = 3, and then .15x = 2.55, so x = 17.</p>', 1001),
(1613, 0, 484303, 'Quant', '', '<p>In an election, 60,000 votes were cast. Every voter picked either Arthur or Beatrice.  Arthur received 600 more votes than Beatrice.  What percent of the votes was cast for Arthur?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-Q20', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  Let a = the number of votes for Arthur and b = the number of votes for Beatrice.  Then a + b = 60,000.Since Arthur received 600 more votes than Beatrice, we can write this as   a = 600 + b .  By substitution into the first equation, we get (600 + b) + b = 60,000   which becomes  600 + 2b = 60,000 , and  2b = 59,400 and so b = 29,700.Beatrice received 29,700 votes, and Arthur received 30,300.  The percent of votes for Arthur was 30,300/60,000 = 50.5%, Choice (C).</p>', 1001),
(1614, 0, 576202, 'Quant', '', '<p>Quantity A:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Quantity B:&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The number of ways to&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(103, 106, 108);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">125</span><!--EndFragment--><br><span style="color: inherit;">arrange five people in a line</span></p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q1', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  The first position in the line can be filled with any of the 5 people.  The second position can be filled with any of the 4 remaining people, the third position with any of the 3 remaining people, etc.  The number of permutations, therefore, is 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 120.  Compare this with Quantity B, 125, and you see that Quantity B is greater.</p>', 1001),
(1615, 0, 760782, 'Quant', '', '<p><span id="docs-internal-guid-4fb919ac-7fff-cb58-1fa1-ceef3eaa0c1e"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: transparent;">Max is designing a rectangular label for the outside of a cylindrical can. &nbsp;The can has a radius of 1.5 inches and a height of 4 inches.</span></span></p>\n<p><font color="#000000"><span id="docs-internal-guid-b6096bb6-7fff-1e36-b2e9-f1bd7a4dacc2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: transparent;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Quantity A:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B:</span><!--EndFragment--><br>The numerical value of the area&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">The numerical value of the&nbsp;</span></span></span></font></p>\n<p><font color="#000000"><span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: transparent;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">of the label in square inches&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;perimeter of the label in inches</span><!--EndFragment--></span></span></font></p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q2', '<p>he correct answer is (A). To find the area and the perimeter of the rectangular label, we need to know its length. The length of the base will be equivalent to the circumference of the can.  C = 2?r where r is the radius of the can.  C = 2?r = 2(?)(1.5) = 3? inches.The area of the label is the base times the height or (3?)(4) = 12? square inches.The perimeter of the label is equal to 2(base + height) = 2(3? + 4) = 6? + 8 inches. Now we can compare the numerical values.  12? ?? 6? + 86? &gt; 8, because ? &gt; 3 and thus 6? &gt; 18 &gt; 8.Quantity A is greater</p>', 1001),
(1616, 0, 800294, 'Quant', '', '<p><span id="docs-internal-guid-11bc61fc-7fff-1baa-b1ae-db7d80e3f35a"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: transparent;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Quantity A:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B:</span><!--EndFragment--><br>The number of prime&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">&nbsp;The number of prime numbers&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\n<p><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">numbers between 10 and 20&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">between 20 and 30</span></p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q3', '<p>The correct answer is (A). A prime number is a positive integer greater than 1, which is divisible only by itself and 1.Let\'s calculate the number of prime numbers between 10 and 20. Any even numbers within the range are NOT prime, because they are divisible by 2. Remaining numbers are 11, 13, 15, 17, and 19.15 = 3 × 5 , so it is NOT prime.The rest are prime. Thus, there are four prime numbers between 10 and 20.Let\'s calculate the number of prime numbers between 20 and 30. Any even numbers within the range are NOT prime, because they are divisible by 2. Remaining numbers are 21, 23, 25, 27, and 29.21 = 3 × 7 , so it is NOT prime.25 = 5 × 5 , so it is NOT prime.27 = 3 × 9 , so it is NOT prime.23 and 29 are prime.Thus there are only two prime numbers between 20 and 30.Quantity A is greater.</p>', 1001),
(1617, 0, 946898, 'Quant', '', '<p><span id="docs-internal-guid-285e1d35-7fff-2471-f37e-b876488fdb47"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: transparent;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Quantity A:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B:<span>&nbsp;</span></span><!--EndFragment--><br>The number of distinct&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </span></span><span style="background-color: transparent;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">The number of distinct&nbsp;</span></p>\n<p style="color: rgb(103, 106, 108);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: transparent;">&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">prime factors of 10&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;prime factors of 40</span></span></p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q4', '<p>Prime-factor the both numbers.10 = 2 × 5    40 = 2 × 2 × 2 × 5There are only two distinct prime factors in each case: 2 and 5. So the quantities are equal.</p>', 1001),
(1618, 0, 312091, 'Quant', '', '<p>The angles ACB and EDB are 90 degrees each. ED = 3, DB = 4, CE = 3, AC = 6 . What is the length of AB?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q5', '<p>The correct answer is (D). The triangle EBD is a right triangle with legs 3 and 4. Thus this is a 3-4-5 triangle and the hypotenuse, EB, is 5 (or you can use the Pythagorean theorem instead).CB = CE + EBCB = 3 + 5CB = 8   The triangle ACB is a right triangle with legs 6 and 8. Thus this is a 3-4-5 triangle and the hypotenuse, AB, is 10 (or you can use the Pythagorean theorem instead).The correct answer is D.</p>', 1001),
(1619, 0, 829987, 'Quant', '', '<p>Let #x denote the greatest integer less than or equal to x.    Quantity A:                                        Quantity B: #3.1 + #(-3.1)                                              0</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q6', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  #3.1 says to find the greatest integer less than 3.1, which is 3.#(-3.1) says to find the greatest integer less than -3.1, which is -4. Their sum, Quantity A,  is (3) + (-4) = -1.  Since 0 &gt; -1, Quantity B is greater.</p>', 1001),
(1620, 0, 111639, 'Quant', '', '<p>A and B are the points where the line AB crosses the axes in the rectangular coordinate system. The equation of the line AB is y = (-4/3)x + 8. What are the coordinates of the point B, which lies on the x-axis?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q7', '<p>The correct answer is (E). The point B lies on the x-axis, so its y-coordinate is 0: B(b, 0). Plug it in the equation:0 = (-4/3)b + 8    b = 8 / (4/3)     b = 6So the coordinates of B are (6, 0) . The correct answer is E</p>', 1001),
(1621, 0, 378248, 'Quant', '', '<p>What number, when decreased by 7, equals 5 times itself?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q8', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  Let\'s designate the number as x.  Then, when we decrease it by 7, we have (x – 7), and this expression is equal to 5x.The equation becomes (x – 7) = 5x.  Solving for x, we get -7 = 4x, and x = -7/4, choice (B).</p>', 1001),
(1622, 0, 564486, 'Quant', '', '<p>In a rectangular coordinate system, what is the area of a rectangle whose vertices have the coordinates (2,-2), (2, 2), (15, 2), (15,-2)?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q9', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  We should start by making a rough sketch of the rectangle.  We can then see that the sides are parallel to the axis so they are easy to calculate.The length of the rectangle is 15 – 2 = 13 units and the width is 2 – (-2) = 4 units. The area of a rectangle is the product of its length and width:  A = 13(4) = 52    The correct answer is A.</p>', 1001),
(1623, 0, 112147, 'Quant', '', '<p>If 20 – ?x = 11, then what are possible values of x?-81, -9, 3, 9, 81</p>', 5, 'Test4-Sec2-Q10', '<p>The correct answer is 81.  Let\'s solve the equation 20 – ?x = 11 by combining and rearranging.  We get 9 = ?x.  Squaring both sides results in 81 = x, and this is the only value that x can take on.</p>', 1001),
(1624, 0, 807159, 'Quant', '', '<p>A dress is bought by a retailer at a cost of $40.00 and is marked up by 80% of its cost.  It is later put on sale, and the selling price is reduced by 20%.  It still doesn’t sell, so it is reduced 30% further from the reduced selling price.  The dress sells at this price.  To the nearest percent, what percent of the original cost of the dress is his profit?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q11', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  The beginning selling price of the dress is  (40) + (40)(.80) = $72.00.The first markdown is (72)(.20) = $14.40, so the dress is priced at $57.60 after the first markdown.The next markdown is (57.60)(.30) = $17.28, resulting in a final reduced selling price of $40.32.His profit is $.32, which, expressed as a percent of the original cost of the dress, is (.32)/40 = 0.008, which equals 0.8 %, which rounds (to the nearest percent) to 1%.</p>', 1001),
(1625, 0, 297961, 'Quant', '', '<p>Sarah and Alice both work at an auto shop, where they are responsible for changing the oil in cars.  It takes Sarah 12 minutes to do one oil change, while it takes Alice only 10 minutes.  If there are lots of cars that need their oil changed, and Sarah and Alice both start doing oil changes at exactly 9:00 A.M., and start the next car as soon as they finish changing the oil in another car, what is the first possible time that they will finish changing the oil of a car simultaneously?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q12', '<p>The correct answer is (A).   Since Sarah will finish s oil changes after (s × 12) minutes and Alice will finish c oil changes after (c × 10) minutes, they both will finish doing an oil change at the same time when s × 12 = c × 10.Since s and c must be integers (they represent the number of oil changes finished) this question is asking you to find a common multiple of 12 and 10.  The question asks for the first time they will finish a car simultaneously, so you must find the least common multiple.The least common multiple of 12 and 10 is 60, so in the context of the question, this would be 60 minutes, or one hour. Therefore, the first time they will finish changing the oil of a car at the same time is 9:00 a.m. + 1 hour, or 10:00 a.m</p>', 1001),
(1626, 0, 128249, 'Quant', '', '<p>A scale drawing of a rectangular garden plot measures 5 inches by 7 inches.  If the longer side of the garden plot is 21 feet, what is the area, in square feet, of the actual garden plot?  </p>', 5, 'Test4-Sec2-Q13', '<p>The correct answer is 315.  You can solve this quickly by setting up a ratio:5/7 = x/21        Cross multiplying yields 105 = 7x, so x = 15, which is the width.Now find the area = length × width, and you get area = (21)(15) = 315 square feet.</p>', 1001),
(1627, 0, 172814, 'Quant', '', '<p>The graphic displays the details of Audrey\'s investment portfolio.  The portfolio\'s value is $766,400. How much money is invested in preferred stocks?</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1530595047.jpg"/></p>', 1, 'test4-Sec2-Q14', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  The percent of preferred stocks is 18% of the entire portfolio, so 766,400 × .18 = $137,952.</p>', 1001),
(1628, 0, 509500, 'Quant', '', '<p>The graphic displays the details of Audrey\'s investment portfolio.  The portfolio\'s value is $766,400. The common stocks are composed of 4 types of stocks:  Blue Chip Stocks: 42%,   Small Cap Stocks: 23%,   Foreign Stocks: 20%, and Penny Stocks: 15%.  What percent of the entire portfolio consists of Small Cap Stocks? (Round the answer to a percent)</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q15', '<p>The correct answer is (C). Common Stocks make 48% of the entire portfolio, which is 0.48 × Total.Small Cap Stocks make 23% of Common Stocks, which is 0.23 × (0.48 × Total). Thus Small Cap Stocks make 0.1104 × Total, which is 11.04% of the entire portfolio.  11.04% rounds to 11% . The correct answer is C.</p>', 1001),
(1629, 0, 449748, 'Quant', '', '<p>Three pandas eat bamboo at three different rates: two pounds per hour, four pounds per hour and ten pounds per hour, respectively.  In 20 minutes how many pounds of bamboo do the two slowest pandas eat, combined?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q16', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  To determine how much a panda eats in 20 minutes the amount of time is multiplied by the rate.In twenty minutes the slowest panda eats: (20 minutes) × (2 pounds / 60 minutes) = (2/3) pound.In twenty minutes the second slowest panda eats:  (20 minutes) × (4 pounds / 60 minutes) = (4/3) pound.The  combined amount eaten by the two slowest pandas is (2/3) pound + (4/3) pound = 2 pounds.</p>', 1001),
(1630, 0, 872964, 'Quant', '', '<p>The girls\' track team has 13 members.  What is the probability that at least two of the girls share the same birth month?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q17', '<p>The correct answer is (E).  The most extreme case is if all of the girls have the same birth month, which, of course, satisfies the requirement.  So let\'s consider the least extreme case, where the girls are spread out as much as possible among the 12 months.  This would mean that each month would have a girl, but since there are 13 girls, we would have one girl left over, putting her into any month; it doesn\'t matter, because whatever month is her birth month, it will have 2 girls in it. The probability, then, that at least 2 girls share the same birth month is 1, a certain event.</p>', 1001),
(1631, 0, 962853, 'Quant', '', '<p>The girls\' track team has 13 members.  What is the probability that at least two of the girls share the same birth month?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q18', '<p>The correct answer is (E).  The most extreme case is if all of the girls have the same birth month, which, of course, satisfies the requirement.  So let\'s consider the least extreme case, where the girls are spread out as much as possible among the 12 months.  This would mean that each month would have a girl, but since there are 13 girls, we would have one girl left over, putting her into any month; it doesn\'t matter, because whatever month is her birth month, it will have 2 girls in it. The probability, then, that at least 2 girls share the same birth month is 1, a certain event.</p>', 1001),
(1632, 0, 855202, 'Quant', '', '<p>If electricity costs x cents per kilowatt-hour for the first 30 kilowatt-hours, and y cents per kilowatt-hour for each additional kilowatt-hour, what is the total cost, in cents, of z kilowatt-hours, where z &gt; 30?</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec2-Q19', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  From the given information, you can establish that it costs 30x cents for the first 30 kilowatt-hours.Since we are trying to determine the total cost of z kilowatt-hours, but we have already determined the cost of the first 30 kilowatt-hours, we just have to determine the cost of the remaining (z – 30) kilowatt-hours at a rate of y cents per kilowatt-hour. This cost is  (z – 30)y cents.Therefore, the total cost in cents is:30x + (z – 30)y . The correct answer is A.</p>', 1001),
(1634, 0, 535814, 'Verbal', '', '<p>In a ______________ statement issued by the Federal Reserve, the Board expressed doubt about the effectiveness of the new law to contain inflation.  The spokeswoman took no questions, and the press conference was over as soon as it began.</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ1', '<p>Credited answer is terse\nThe passage describes a very brief press conference.  Whatever comments were shared by the spokeswoman, they must have been brief, too.  Terse means short and to the point, which fits the context.\n</p>', 1001),
(1635, 0, 925949, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Faced with limited options when constructing the Suez Canal, the builders were ______________ to blast a ninety foot deep passage through rock.</p>', 1, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ2', '<p>Your Choice: impoliticCredited Answer: obligedObliged means compelled to do something; here the builders were forced to blast a channel.</p>', 1001),
(1636, 2, 624861, 'Verbal', '', '<p>&#34;There I was, ______________ to the kids\' table for the big family dinner.  I was so, like, annoyed,&#34; said one sixteen-year-old to another.  &#34;You should have been thankful,&#34; said the other, &#34;I was at the adults\' table and had to listen to hours of boring conversation...how ______________!&#34;</p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ3', '<p>Credited Answers: (i) relegated   (ii) tediousTo be relegated is to be dismissed to an inferior position, which is what the first teenager was annoyed about.  The second thought his situation worse, listening to dull, or tedious, adult conversation.</p>', 1001),
(1637, 2, 791619, 'Verbal', '', '<p>As dictators go, Kang was rather ______________.  He insisted on fair laws and trials for his people, his ministers were responsive to public concerns, and he was never ______________ or cruel. </p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ4', '<p>Credited Answers: (i) benign       (ii) repressiveDictators have a general reputation of being tyrannical and unpopular.  This passage describes a dictator who, unlike most, is kindly, or benign, as opposed to cruel.  The second blank is for some negative quality which did not describe Kang: the only fitting choice is repressive (to repress means to subdue).</p>', 1001),
(1638, 2, 573900, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Courage is not found only in the mature.  Consider the ______________ first grader returning to school the day after being mercilessly teased, or a friend with the ______________ to come to the rescue in that situation.</p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ5', '<p>Since Stern worked for several shows, it is logical to assume his career was prolific, full of output.  A word game could have a creator, or architect, but not a wrangler or adversary.  Since the game has to do with various parts of speech, is must be a phrasal template game.</p>', 1001),
(1639, 3, 860702, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Although Lenard Stern had a (i) ______________ career as a writer and producer for numerous television shows, he is most distinguished as the (ii) ______________ of Mad Libs, the (iii) ______________ template game that invited one player to prompt the other for answers based exclusively on designated parts of speech.</p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ6', '<p>Credited Answers:(i) prolific(ii) architect(iii) phrasalSince Stern worked for several shows, it is logical to assume his career was prolific, full of output.  A word game could have a creator, or architect, but not a wrangler or adversary.  Since the game has to do with various parts of speech, is must be a phrasal template game.</p>', 1001),
(1640, 0, 241595, 'Verbal', '<p>There are numerous theories about the meteoric rise in the gold market, and coordinating ascent of other precious metals, including the reluctance of investors to risk capital in unstable equities and a general historic correlation with the increase of the price of oil.</p>', '<p>The phrase “coordinating ascent” most closely means</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ7', '<p>Credited Answer: DThe correct answer is (D).  Since the same factors which drive up the price of gold are likely to drive up the price of other metals, the closest meaning is (D). The term is describing the metals, not investors, so (A) is wrong. While the other metals are described as precious, the phrase describes their price, not their type or style, eliminating (B).  The phrase is specifically describing the rise in prices, not the grouping of the prices, so (C) does not work. Choice (E) describes both increasing and decreasing, and the phrase describes only the ascent, or increase.</p>', 1001),
(1641, 0, 479530, 'Verbal', '<p>As the replacement for the defunct League of Nations, the United Nations was chartered in 1945 to encourage nations to work toward peaceful international relations.  Since then, it has maintained an emphasis on diminishing potential conflicts by addressing the broader social issues that often result in heightened tensions.  It has also incorporated human rights into its agenda through the creation of the Universal Declaration of Human rights in 1948, which is the foundational treaty in contemporary human rights law and defines the basic entitlements of all people.  Since then, the United Nations has expanded its mission to address global concerns such as eradicating poverty and hunger, promoting gender equality, fostering environmental sustainability and engendering global partnerships for development.  These millennium developmental goals represent the evolution of the organization\'s priorities, and current belief that the sources of conflicts must be specifically addressed. In another expansion of its role, the United Nation is now highly visible in international conflicts.  It sends out armed forces as peacekeepers, often known as the “blue berets,” in war-torn regions.  The United Nations now also plays a pivotal role in post-conflict international justice with the creation of the International Criminal Court (ICC), otherwise known as The Hague, which has tried war criminals and those accused of committing genocide in Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia.  While it is difficult to predict the function of the United Nations fifty years from now, it is evident that the organization will continue to adapt to meet the pressing needs of its constituents.</p>', '<p>What is the main idea of the passage?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ8', '<p>The passage discusses the various roles that the United Nations has adopted in its history, so (A) is the correct answer.  While the passage mentions a military force, it does not suggest it is dominant.  Since the League of Nations ended before the United Nations was founded, the U.N. cannot have been the inspiration for the League of Nations.  There is not enough information about the ICC or its trials for either of those to be the main idea of the passage.</p>', 1001),
(1642, 0, 894578, 'Verbal', '<p>As the replacement for the defunct League of Nations, the United Nations was chartered in 1945 to encourage nations to work toward peaceful international relations.  Since then, it has maintained an emphasis on diminishing potential conflicts by addressing the broader social issues that often result in heightened tensions.  It has also incorporated human rights into its agenda through the creation of the Universal Declaration of Human rights in 1948, which is the foundational treaty in contemporary human rights law and defines the basic entitlements of all people.  Since then, the United Nations has expanded its mission to address global concerns such as eradicating poverty and hunger, promoting gender equality, fostering environmental sustainability and engendering global partnerships for development.  These millennium developmental goals represent the evolution of the organization\'s priorities, and current belief that the sources of conflicts must be specifically addressed. In another expansion of its role, the United Nation is now highly visible in international conflicts.  It sends out armed forces as peacekeepers, often known as the “blue berets,” in war-torn regions.  The United Nations now also plays a pivotal role in post-conflict international justice with the creation of the International Criminal Court (ICC), otherwise known as The Hague, which has tried war criminals and those accused of committing genocide in Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia.  While it is difficult to predict the function of the United Nations fifty years from now, it is evident that the organization will continue to adapt to meet the pressing needs of its constituents.</p>', '<p>What does the passage suggest is the purpose of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ9', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  The Universal Declaration of Human Rights was created to define universal human rights, so (D) is correct.  The passage states that the peacekeeping force, mentioned in Choice (A), came much later, and there is no direct connection between the two. The Universal Declaration\'s purpose is not the enforcement of international treaties, so Choice (B) is incorrect. The Hague, mentioned in Choice (C) is an international court; its purpose is to support some of the principles in the Declaration, but its justification was not the purpose of the Declaration.  While the eradication of genocide (E) is addressed by the United Nations, that is not the focus of the Declaration.</p>', 1001),
(1643, 0, 229375, 'Verbal', '<p>As the replacement for the defunct League of Nations, the United Nations was chartered in 1945 to encourage nations to work toward peaceful international relations.  Since then, it has maintained an emphasis on diminishing potential conflicts by addressing the broader social issues that often result in heightened tensions.  It has also incorporated human rights into its agenda through the creation of the Universal Declaration of Human rights in 1948, which is the foundational treaty in contemporary human rights law and defines the basic entitlements of all people.  Since then, the United Nations has expanded its mission to address global concerns such as eradicating poverty and hunger, promoting gender equality, fostering environmental sustainability and engendering global partnerships for development.  These millennium developmental goals represent the evolution of the organization\'s priorities, and current belief that the sources of conflicts must be specifically addressed. In another expansion of its role, the United Nation is now highly visible in international conflicts.  It sends out armed forces as peacekeepers, often known as the “blue berets,” in war-torn regions.  The United Nations now also plays a pivotal role in post-conflict international justice with the creation of the International Criminal Court (ICC), otherwise known as The Hague, which has tried war criminals and those accused of committing genocide in Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia.  While it is difficult to predict the function of the United Nations fifty years from now, it is evident that the organization will continue to adapt to meet the pressing needs of its constituents</p>', '<p>According to the passage, what is the function of The Hague?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ10', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  The passage explicitly states that the ICC, or International Criminal Court, is the function of The Hague.  All other answers represent priorities of the United Nations, but not The Hague specifically.</p>', 1001),
(1644, 0, 120409, 'Verbal', '<p>As the replacement for the defunct League of Nations, the United Nations was chartered in 1945 to encourage nations to work toward peaceful international relations.  Since then, it has maintained an emphasis on diminishing potential conflicts by addressing the broader social issues that often result in heightened tensions.  It has also incorporated human rights into its agenda through the creation of the Universal Declaration of Human rights in 1948, which is the foundational treaty in contemporary human rights law and defines the basic entitlements of all people.  Since then, the United Nations has expanded its mission to address global concerns such as eradicating poverty and hunger, promoting gender equality, fostering environmental sustainability and engendering global partnerships for development.  These millennium developmental goals represent the evolution of the organization\'s priorities, and current belief that the sources of conflicts must be specifically addressed. In another expansion of its role, the United Nation is now highly visible in international conflicts.  It sends out armed forces as peacekeepers, often known as the “blue berets,” in war-torn regions.  The United Nations now also plays a pivotal role in post-conflict international justice with the creation of the International Criminal Court (ICC), otherwise known as The Hague, which has tried war criminals and those accused of committing genocide in Rwanda and the former Yugoslavia.  While it is difficult to predict the function of the United Nations fifty years from now, it is evident that the organization will continue to adapt to meet the pressing needs of its constituents.</p>', '<p>Which of the following is not a function of the United Nations stated in the passage?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ11', '<p>The correct answer is (E).  While part of the accomplishment of the millennial goals might require funding infrastructure development, this detail is not included in the passage.  All of the other answers are explicitly stated as roles of the United Nations.</p>', 1001),
(1645, 1, 542950, 'Verbal', '', '<p>While the ______________ shoot-out at the O.K. Corral has been dramatized in several books and films, reexaminations reveal that the fight had more to do with local political tensions than previously assumed.</p>', 2, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ12', '<p>The fact that it is a shooting suggests that the association will not be positive, eliminating heralded, reverent, and genuine.  Trifling means insignificant, and given the level of attention given to the fight, this is not applicable; therefore, infamous and notorious are the answers.</p>', 1001),
(1646, 0, 907967, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Because the ______________ of the zebra’s skin is black, the zebra is most accurately described as black with white stripes.</p>', 2, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ13', '<p>Credited Answer(s): coloration, pigmentationThe question is about color, so coloration and pigmentation are the correct answers.  Consistency has to do with texture, taciturn means silent, and tactile relates to touch. Premeditation means consideration beforehand, which doesn’t apply to a zebra’s skin.</p>', 1001),
(1647, 0, 487685, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Residents of Kenya express growing concern over the apparently endless ______________ of refugees fleeing neighboring Somalia.</p>', 2, 'Test3-Sec1-VQ14', '<p>Credited Answer(s):  deluge, hordesThe phrase “apparently endless” indicates that there is a large quantity of refugees, eliminating dearth and deficiency, both of which suggest a lack.  Articulation refers to speech and hoax to deception, so these do not apply.  The answers are deluge and hordes, both of which imply many.</p>', 1001),
(1648, 0, 641313, 'Verbal', '', '<p>After being wrongfully accused of theft, the irate man complained of his treatment during the interrogation, with a comment to the journalist: “That kind of ______________ is totally uncalled for!”.</p>', 2, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ15', '<p>Credited Answer(s):denigration,disparagementBoth disparagement and denigration imply a demeaning of one\'s character, which might happen during an unfair interrogation.  Deliberation (discussion) would not make a man irate, nor would mitigation (lessening), articulation (making a succinct statement), or peregrination (travel).</p>', 1001);
INSERT INTO `tbl_question_new` (`id`, `noofblanks`, `trackid`, `category`, `paragraph`, `name`, `question_type_id`, `note`, `solution`, `status`) VALUES
(1649, 0, 502261, 'Verbal', '<p>The increased potential for fiscal mismanagement is a sobering thought considering the influx of baby boomers to America’s senior populations.  Financial responsibility, like other essential skills, deteriorates with age, and the unwillingness of aging elders to relinquish control compounds the problem.  While the deleterious effect of maturing on other behaviors, such as driving, is well documented, pecuniary habits have not been extensively studied.  However, the discomfiture associated with honest assessment of abilities is highly likely to impact this aspect of personal maintenance as well.  Since seniors control over a third of the nation’s wealth, there are valid reasons for concern.</p>', '<p>Which of the following best summarizes the passage?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ16', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  While (A) is true, it is a detail from the passage rather than its main idea.  There is no discussion of gender differences, so (B) is incorrect.  Since there are no recommendations in the passage, (C) cannot be the answer. Choice (E) is not validated in the passage.  Answer (D), as stated in both the opening and closing sentences, best summarizes the point of the passage.</p>', 1001),
(1650, 0, 781719, 'Verbal', '<p>Entrepreneurially-minded employees are driven by independence, risk taking, innovation and reward. Because they are so highly valued by employers, many people with an entrepreneurial education do not end up as business owners.An employer who creates the right kind of environment can keep entrepreneurs on board for the long-term and help them produce their most innovative work. Rewards, such as bonuses or equity for hard work, get at the heart of what the entrepreneur’s mind needs: challenge and incentive.  In addition to financial incentives, entrepreneurs often choose to work for someone because an employer may offer learning opportunities unavailable otherwise. Working for a company that offers financial incentives, while at the same time teaching invaluable business skills, can be rewarding. For many graduates of entrepreneurship programs, this combination is difficult to pass up. Most graduates of the Entrepreneurial Studies Institute at the University of Michigan do not immediately start their own companies, but instead take corporate jobs after graduation. After a decade of working, more than half still do not own their own businesses.Though some business owners shy away from hiring entrepreneurially-minded employees, the ingenuity and flexibility of these workers make them valuable assets to any business.</p>', '<p>Based on the information presented in the passage, the author would be most likely to agree that companies interested in hiring entrepreneurs should do which of the following?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ17', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  Choice (A) may be self-evident, but it is not referred to in the passage. Similarly, there is nothing in the passage to suggest that entrepreneurs care about any of choices (B), (C) or (E), or that they are an issue in any way. But (D) relates to the author’s opinion that it is important to reward entrepreneurs for their hard work in order to keep them motivated.</p>', 1001),
(1652, 0, 301354, 'Verbal', '<p>Entrepreneurially-minded employees are driven by independence, risk taking, innovation and reward. Because they are so highly valued by employers, many people with an entrepreneurial education do not end up as business owners.An employer who creates the right kind of environment can keep entrepreneurs on board for the long-term and help them produce their most innovative work. Rewards, such as bonuses or equity for hard work, get at the heart of what the entrepreneur’s mind needs: challenge and incentive.  In addition to financial incentives, entrepreneurs often choose to work for someone because an employer may offer learning opportunities unavailable otherwise. Working for a company that offers financial incentives, while at the same time teaching invaluable business skills, can be rewarding. For many graduates of entrepreneurship programs, this combination is difficult to pass up. Most graduates of the Entrepreneurial Studies Institute at the University of Michigan do not immediately start their own companies, but instead take corporate jobs after graduation. After a decade of working, more than half still do not own their own businesses.Though some business owners shy away from hiring entrepreneurially-minded employees, the ingenuity and flexibility of these workers make them valuable assets to any business.</p>', '<p>Which of the following is a purpose of the passage?I. To champion entrepreneurs as valuable employeesII. To deride employers who do not hire entrepreneursIII. To explain what motivates entrepreneurs to work</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ18', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  The passage details the many positive attributes of entrepreneurs and the unique skills that they bring to a workplace, so Statement I is correct. It also explains two motivators for entrepreneurs, so Statement III is correct. The author mentions in the last paragraph that some businesses shy away from hiring entrepreneurs and there is, perhaps, an implication that such employers lack the vision or boldness to attract these valuable employees, but any such criticism does not rise to the level of derision. Therefore, II is wrong and only I and III are correct.</p>', 1001),
(1653, 0, 978115, 'Verbal', '<p>Entrepreneurially-minded employees are driven by independence, risk taking, innovation and reward. Because they are so highly valued by employers, many people with an entrepreneurial education do not end up as business owners.An employer who creates the right kind of environment can keep entrepreneurs on board for the long-term and help them produce their most innovative work. Rewards, such as bonuses or equity for hard work, get at the heart of what the entrepreneur’s mind needs: challenge and incentive.  In addition to financial incentives, entrepreneurs often choose to work for someone because an employer may offer learning opportunities unavailable otherwise. Working for a company that offers financial incentives, while at the same time teaching invaluable business skills, can be rewarding. For many graduates of entrepreneurship programs, this combination is difficult to pass up. Most graduates of the Entrepreneurial Studies Institute at the University of Michigan do not immediately start their own companies, but instead take corporate jobs after graduation. After a decade of working, more than half still do not own their own businesses.Though some business owners shy away from hiring entrepreneurially-minded employees, the ingenuity and flexibility of these workers make them valuable assets to any business.</p>', '<p>The passage suggests that which of the following is the most likely reason why graduates of the entrepreneurial program at the University of Michigan would still be working for companies after 10 years?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ19', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  The third paragraph follows two paragraphs that describe the benefits that the author believes some entrepreneurs find in working for others. There is no evidence for choices (A), (D), (C) or (E) anywhere in the passage. The passage argues that equity offers and engaging opportunities will keep employees working hard for the long term. The theme of the essay is that entrepreneurs are driven by challenge and financial incentive, and choice (B) fits within this framework. </p>', 1001),
(1654, 0, 961895, 'Verbal', '<p>Entrepreneurially-minded employees are driven by independence, risk taking, innovation and reward. Because they are so highly valued by employers, many people with an entrepreneurial education do not end up as business owners.An employer who creates the right kind of environment can keep entrepreneurs on board for the long-term and help them produce their most innovative work. Rewards, such as bonuses or equity for hard work, get at the heart of what the entrepreneur’s mind needs: challenge and incentive.  In addition to financial incentives, entrepreneurs often choose to work for someone because an employer may offer learning opportunities unavailable otherwise. Working for a company that offers financial incentives, while at the same time teaching invaluable business skills, can be rewarding. For many graduates of entrepreneurship programs, this combination is difficult to pass up. Most graduates of the Entrepreneurial Studies Institute at the University of Michigan do not immediately start their own companies, but instead take corporate jobs after graduation. After a decade of working, more than half still do not own their own businesses.Though some business owners shy away from hiring entrepreneurially-minded employees, the ingenuity and flexibility of these workers make them valuable assets to any business.</p>', '<p>Which of the following statements, if true, most seriously undermines the reasoning in the representative\'s argument?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec1-VQ20', '<p>The correct answer is (C). This question asks you to find the statement that most seriously undermines the reasoning in the argument.  The argument consists of a state representative\'s response to criticism regarding the inadequacy of their prison facilities. The representative attempts to counter this charge by saying that the state will allocate a lot of money to the prison in the coming year.  A statement that undermines this reasoning will suggest a way in which this relatively high spending level does not equate to adequate facilities.  Choice (A) presents unrelated information; we are concerned with the prison system in this state, not those in neighboring states.  Choice (B) suggests a reason why the prison facilities may be inadequate: if there has been a recent increase in felony convictions, then there may be more inmates than the system can handle.  This appears to undermine the representative\'s argument insofar that it shows that the critics were likely justified in calling the facilities inadequate.  However, we don\'t know how the increase in felony convictions actually affected the total number of inmates in the system; without this additional information, the statement in choice (B) can have no effect on the argument.  Choice (C) shows a way in which a high spending level may not signify adequate facilities. If the state allocates more money to the prison system than to other projects next year, then it must be true that the state\'s prison facilities have remained inadequate despite the efforts of the past few years. The discussion of funding should set off alarm bells because good funding does not equate with good results. Choice (D) is irrelevant; the prisons’ rehabilitation efforts are not in question.  Choice (E) has no effect on the argument; even if we agree that the state should not use their money in this way, a statement of opinion can have no bearing on an argument\'s logical structure.  Choice (C) most seriously undermines the representative\'s argument, and is the best choice.</p>', 1001),
(1655, 1, 154709, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Nothing is more harmful to a republic than elected officials exceeding their authority and assuming ______________ powers.</p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ1', '<p>Your Choice: undefinedCredited Answer: arbitraryOnly the word arbitrary fits the context of an official going beyond his mandate and taking on extra powers.  Arbitrary in this context means undemocratic, unrestrained.</p>', 1001),
(1656, 1, 786926, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Though in September the two regional satellite radio companies announced their intention of merging , the Federal Trade Commission as of late November had not given ______________ to the plan.</p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ2', '<p>Your Choice: undefinedCredited Answer: sanctionThough a sanction can be a penalty, a second meaning is official approval.  Here, the companies await official sanction from the government agency overseeing their industry.</p>', 1001),
(1657, 2, 509306, 'Verbal', '', '<p>British writers had no hesitation in calling him a ______________ tyrant.  No matter Bonaparte\'s legal reforms or grand state projects, he was an enemy, he was unscrupulous in occupied territory, and he exercised control as an oppressive ______________.</p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ3', '<p>Credited Answer(s):(i)  nefarious(ii)  despotNefarious means wicked, the best fit for the first sentence.  A despot is similar to a tyrant, cruelly exercising tremendous political power.</p>', 1001),
(1660, 3, 401178, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Margaret Mitchell left very specific instructions (i) _____________ what topics could be permissibly explored in any published sequel or prequels to her (ii) ______________ work, Gone with the Wind, to ensure that her vision of the characters she created remained (iii) ______________.</p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ6', '<p>Credited Answer(s):(i) delimiting(ii) seminal(iii) safeguardedThe fact that the list is very specific suggests that it delimits or defines what can be written.  If the novel begs to have a sequel or prequel written, it must be influential, or seminal.  Mitchell would be trying to safeguard the integrity of her characters by define</p>', 1001),
(1661, 0, 886656, 'Verbal', '<p>US airlines have been suffering financial strain recently and are looking for new profit generators. The newest item of business: make ticket pricing complicated, so consumers have trouble figuring out what their trips actually cost.The Department of Transportation has been bombarded by airlines asking for advertising rules to be changed so that some costs are not factored into the base price of a ticket. Instead, costs like fuel surcharges would be calculated later, making the original advertised price deceptive. It’s true that quoted fares have not been exact fares for quite some time now. Airlines are allowed to split out some government-imposed fees and taxes, but these costs must be shown in advertisements. Now, airlines want their own surcharges to be withheld from advertisements, and instead to present them only near the end of the purchasing process, where consumers may not have enough time to carefully consider prices. If advertising rules change, fictional surcharges will surely emerge aimed at “lowering prices,” obscuring the actual cost of fares. Competition among airlines for low fares could come to be based on surcharges, resulting in airlines falsely making their tickets appear cheaper than those of their competitors. In the end, consumers will lose the ability to make informed choices.</p>', '<p>The passage suggests that fictional surcharges will create profit for airlines by</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ7', '<p>Your Choice: No Answer GivenCredited Answer: BThe correct answer is (B).  Paragraph two states: “Instead costs…are calculated later, making the original advertised price significantly lower than what consumers end up paying for tickets.” Thus, surcharges obscure parts of the total ticket price, making tickets appear cheaper than they actually are and encouraging more air travel. The passage contains no evidence for (A), (C), (D) or (E).</p>', 1001),
(1662, 0, 492272, 'Verbal', '<p>US airlines have been suffering financial strain recently and are looking for new profit generators. The newest item of business: make ticket pricing complicated, so consumers have trouble figuring out what their trips actually cost.The Department of Transportation has been bombarded by airlines asking for advertising rules to be changed so that some costs are not factored into the base price of a ticket. Instead, costs like fuel surcharges would be calculated later, making the original advertised price deceptive. It’s true that quoted fares have not been exact fares for quite some time now. Airlines are allowed to split out some government-imposed fees and taxes, but these costs must be shown in advertisements. Now, airlines want their own surcharges to be withheld from advertisements, and instead to present them only near the end of the purchasing process, where consumers may not have enough time to carefully consider prices. If advertising rules change, fictional surcharges will surely emerge aimed at “lowering prices,” obscuring the actual cost of fares. Competition among airlines for low fares could come to be based on surcharges, resulting in airlines falsely making their tickets appear cheaper than those of their competitors. In the end, consumers will lose the ability to make informed choices.</p>', '<p>The author’s purpose is to</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ8', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  The author criticizes airlines for unfair advertising practices throughout the passage. Therefore, (A) is correct. Choice (B) is not mentioned in the passage. Choice (C) explains a purpose opposite to the author’s. The author believes airlines are taking advantage of consumers and thus he or she does not support the airlines. Choice (D) is only mentioned as a motivation for airlines to advertise lower prices, but the author does not express any interest in this practice. Choice (E) is correct about elements of the passage but it does not sum up the passage’s purpose, because it does not mention any bias.</p>', 1001),
(1663, 0, 927828, 'Verbal', '<p>US airlines have been suffering financial strain recently and are looking for new profit generators. The newest item of business: make ticket pricing complicated, so consumers have trouble figuring out what their trips actually cost.The Department of Transportation has been bombarded by airlines asking for advertising rules to be changed so that some costs are not factored into the base price of a ticket. Instead, costs like fuel surcharges would be calculated later, making the original advertised price deceptive. It’s true that quoted fares have not been exact fares for quite some time now. Airlines are allowed to split out some government-imposed fees and taxes, but these costs must be shown in advertisements. Now, airlines want their own surcharges to be withheld from advertisements, and instead to present them only near the end of the purchasing process, where consumers may not have enough time to carefully consider prices. If advertising rules change, fictional surcharges will surely emerge aimed at “lowering prices,” obscuring the actual cost of fares. Competition among airlines for low fares could come to be based on surcharges, resulting in airlines falsely making their tickets appear cheaper than those of their competitors. In the end, consumers will lose the ability to make informed choices.</p>', '<p>This passage is probably written by a(n)</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ9', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  The author tells us that airlines are taking advantage of consumers by manipulating advertising. He or she is critical of these practices and believes they hurt consumers. Thus, the author cannot be an advocate for the parties causing the problem the passage discusses, so (A) and (D) are wrong. Choice (B) does not fit because a newspaper reporter (as opposed to a commentator) details issues and events in an unbiased fashion. This author has an opinion and makes it known. (E) is wrong because the author never indicates whether the Department of Transportation agrees or disagrees with airline fare advertisement practices. Since the author seems most concerned with protecting consumers, we can conclude that the he or she a consumer advocate.</p>', 1001),
(1664, 0, 781980, 'Verbal', '<p>Historians often emphasize the differences between the developing identities of early New England and Southern United States colonists. While both groups initially considered themselves British subjects first, and only secondarily as residents of their particular geographic region, local identities had clearly gained primacy during the 18th century. While many factors contributed to this emerging identity, certain economic and cultural factors are perhaps the easiest on which to elaborate. Throughout the colonial period, New England maintained a remarkably homogeneous population. Its economy was broad based, consisting mainly of fishing, shipbuilding, manufacturing and farming. Most farming was for subsistence, not profit. On the other hand, the Southern colonies relied mainly on the farming of wealthy large estates known as plantations. These plantations were worked principally by slaves brought from Africa. In the late 18th century, these slaves nearly equaled the number of white colonists in Virginia. In South Carolina, they outnumbered the whites by nearly two-to-one. Not only did the plantations create a class system unknown in New England, but they also changed the nature of local government. In New England, people associated in compact villages, while in the South, plantations spread over so wide an area as to make villages impossible. In New England, the town was the natural unit of government; in the South, the county was all-important. The largely rural character of the South had a pronounced effect on its cultural development.</p>', '<p>The passage suggests that, in the colonial period, the economies of New England and the South differed in which of the following ways?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ10', '<p>The correct answer is (A). The passage discusses economies in the second paragraph. It compares the two regions in the second, third, and fourth sentences. The choice that matches those sentences is (A), since the New England economy is said to have been “broad based,” while the Southern economy relied mainly on farming.All of the other choices may be true, but we’re looking for something directly supported by the passage.  Choice (A) is the only one that does this.</p>', 1001),
(1665, 0, 513981, 'Verbal', '<p>Historians often emphasize the differences between the developing identities of early New England and Southern United States colonists. While both groups initially considered themselves British subjects first, and only secondarily as residents of their particular geographic region, local identities had clearly gained primacy during the 18th century. While many factors contributed to this emerging identity, certain economic and cultural factors are perhaps the easiest on which to elaborate. Throughout the colonial period, New England maintained a remarkably homogeneous population. Its economy was broad based, consisting mainly of fishing, shipbuilding, manufacturing and farming. Most farming was for subsistence, not profit. On the other hand, the Southern colonies relied mainly on the farming of wealthy large estates known as plantations. These plantations were worked principally by slaves brought from Africa. In the late 18th century, these slaves nearly equaled the number of white colonists in Virginia. In South Carolina, they outnumbered the whites by nearly two-to-one. Not only did the plantations create a class system unknown in New England, but they also changed the nature of local government. In New England, people associated in compact villages, while in the South, plantations spread over so wide an area as to make villages impossible. In New England, the town was the natural unit of government; in the South, the county was all-important. The largely rural character of the South had a pronounced effect on its cultural development.</p>', '<p>The passage is primarily concerned with</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ11', '<p>The correct answer is (C). This is a descriptive passage; it doesn’t take a stance on an issue.  That means we can quickly eliminate (B), (D), and (E) simply on the basis of their first words.  The passage doesn’t “advocate,” “argue” or “criticize.”  Choices (A) and (C) are very different.  Does the passage primarily describe similarities or differences?  The second paragraph makes it clear that the focus of the passage is on differences, so choice (C) is correct.</p>', 1001),
(1666, 0, 725585, 'Verbal', '<p>Historians often emphasize the differences between the developing identities of early New England and Southern United States colonists. While both groups initially considered themselves British subjects first, and only secondarily as residents of their particular geographic region, local identities had clearly gained primacy during the 18th century. While many factors contributed to this emerging identity, certain economic and cultural factors are perhaps the easiest on which to elaborate. Throughout the colonial period, New England maintained a remarkably homogeneous population. Its economy was broad based, consisting mainly of fishing, shipbuilding, manufacturing and farming. Most farming was for subsistence, not profit. On the other hand, the Southern colonies relied mainly on the farming of wealthy large estates known as plantations. These plantations were worked principally by slaves brought from Africa. In the late 18th century, these slaves nearly equaled the number of white colonists in Virginia. In South Carolina, they outnumbered the whites by nearly two-to-one. Not only did the plantations create a class system unknown in New England, but they also changed the nature of local government. In New England, people associated in compact villages, while in the South, plantations spread over so wide an area as to make villages impossible. In New England, the town was the natural unit of government; in the South, the county was all-important. The largely rural character of the South had a pronounced effect on its cultural development.</p>', '<p>The passage suggests that the South relied on local government organized at the county level because</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ12', '<p>The correct answer is (D). First, find the relevant sentence in the passage: “In New England, people associated in compact villages while in the South, plantations spread over so wide an area as to make villages impossible.”  In short: plantations were too big for organization at the village level.  Thus choice (D) is correct.  None of the other choices are supported by the passage.</p>', 1001),
(1667, 0, 581543, 'Verbal', '<p>When sales for an Omnimedia-owned home decorating magazine plunged by 30 percent in one month, Omnimedia launched a new crafts magazine to bolster sales. This decision surprised market analysts, because usually when a magazine\'s sales plunge so dramatically, readers will also neglect to purchase a magazine on a closely related topic.</p>', '<p>Which of the following, if true, provides the best indication that Omnimedia\'s decision was logically well supported?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ13', '<p>Choice (A) is out of the scope of the question.(B) This is correct.  Thanks to the success with advertisers, the home decorating magazine is profitable. Thus the crafts magazine, presumably without the marketing flaw, may also be profitable. (C) Without knowing the reason behind the sales decline at the home decorating magazine, there\'s no reason to think that shifting staff members explains Omnimedia\'s decision.(D) A slight increase in subscriptions is not enough to explain launching another magazine, especially since it is contrasted with a sharp decline in newsstand sales.(E) The prior track record doesn’t indicate future success.</p>', 1001),
(1668, 0, 115344, 'Verbal', '<p>Critic: Some historians claim that the people who built this ring of stones thousands of years ago in England were knowledgeable about celestial events. This is not the case. The historians base their claim on the fact that two of the stones in the ring form a line pointing directly to the position of the sun at sunrise at the spring equinox. However, there are so many stones in the ring that the chance of at least one pair pointing in a celestially significant direction is high.</p>', '<p>The critic’s conclusion is questionable because</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2_VQ', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  The problem with the critic’s conclusion is that he goes too far in stating categorically that the builders of the ring were not informed about celestial matters. The undermining of evidence offered in support of a statement does not prove the opposite of that statement. Just because the historians may have based their claim on flawed evidence does not mean that the opposite of their claim is true. Choices (B), (C) and (D) are merely smokescreens designed to confuse you: none accurately describes the process by which the critic reached his conclusion. (E) may be true, but the critic’s conclusion is founded on a fallacy in the historians’ thinking, not on any pretense of superior historical or scientific knowledge.</p>', 1001),
(1669, 0, 704613, 'Verbal', '<p>Columnist: The mayor’s opponents claim that the questions surrounding the vice-mayor’s tax return make the mayor unfit to be re-elected. The vice-mayor, however, was directly elected by the public in an election prior to the election that put the mayor into office. Furthermore, the vice-mayor’s faulty tax return can be clearly traced to an innocent error made by an accountant and it sheds no light on the ability of the vice-mayor to perform his duties. </p>', '<p>Which of the following best describes the main point of the argument? </p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ15', '<p>The correct answer is (D). With main point questions, you’re asked to separate the point of an argument from the reasons supporting that point. The pundit’s motive may be to help get the mayor re-elected, but he nowhere claims that the mayor is fit to be re-elected, merely that her opponents have fabricated their expressed reason for finding her unfit. Therefore, choice (A) is too broad. The passage isn’t saying how great the vice-mayor is, just how flawed the opponent\'s’ argument is. (B) Simply negating the accounting issue does not equate with the vice-mayor\'s being qualified. Although (C) is a possible additional argument, it isn’t stated here. Choice (E) is going beyond the passage because perhaps the accountant was hired improperly. Saying the vice-mayor was not at fault is different from saying he is not unfit for office. Further, this is secondary to the main issue, which is (D).</p>', 1001),
(1670, 0, 496633, 'Verbal', '<p>The success rate of pianists trained at The Belmont School is twice that of pianists trained at other schools.  This must be due to the quality of instruction offered at this school.</p>', '<p>Which of the following, if true, would LEAST weaken the argument?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ16', '<p>The correct answer is (C). This answer does the least to weaken the argument.  Since the argument concludes that the Belmont students’ rate of professional success must be due to the quality of instruction offered at the school, we can eliminate any answer choice that suggests there might be another explanation for their success.  Note that it is not necessary to prove that another factor is responsible for the success rate, merely that another factor could be responsible.Choices (A), (D) and (E) provide alternative explanations for the students’ professional success.  If the school is competitive to begin with (A), then it is likely that only the best students will be admitted to this school.  If it is also true that students who are talented to begin with are more likely to achieve success, then this could explain why students who graduate from this school are more successful.  Similarly, if the students all have an usually high musical aptitude (D), or have been required to take business courses (E), then it could be more likely that they will succeed professionally.  Choice (B) weakens the argument by directly contradicting the conclusion.  If pianists trained at The Belmont School achieve greater success than those trained at any other school, and if their greater success is due to the quality of instruction offered at the school, then the school must offer some of the best instruction in the country.  Choice (B) tells us that this is not the case; instead, it is the school’s generous spending that is among the best in the country.  Unlike the other choices, choice (C) has no effect on the argument.  The fact that only two pianists trained at The Belmont School have achieved international success tells us nothing about the success of all Belmont School pianists relative to those who graduated from other schools.  It could very well be the case that these were the only pianists in the country to have achieved international success in the last thirty years.  (C) is the only answer that does not weaken the argument.</p>', 1001),
(1671, 0, 170695, 'Verbal', '<p>A shift towards increased reliance on nuclear energy in 21st-century America has intrigued many energy policy makers ever since the threat of diminishing fossil fuel reserves became apparent. Despite the drawbacks, some energy specialists endorse the idea, finding a hidden benefit in the fact that nuclear power plants cause no increase in greenhouse gas emissions. Others, however, contend that these are merely ancillary factors when the overall effects of increased nuclear power generation on the environment are considered. This alternative outlook concludes that the nuclear perspective, by focusing solely on decreases in fossil fuel reliance and greenhouse emissions, is based on the evaluation of only trivial considerations. This anti-nuclear view is currently the prevailing one, emphasizing the many negative environmental consequences of an increased reliance on nuclear energy.The central reasons for renewed interest in nuclear power plants come from entirely different considerations. Because the U.S. imports over 50 percent of its oil from foreign nations, including many in the Middle East, experts claim that an increased reliance on nuclear power would both bestow financial benefits on the national economy and advance the nation’s goal of energy independence. Moreover, they point to the political benefits that would accrue if the U.S. was no longer forced to obtain its energy supply from nations with unstable or antagonistic regimes. Increased reliance on nuclear power, therefore, would improve both the financial and geopolitical status of the United States.Although correctly evaluating these factors, this analysis ignores the environmental implications of an increased reliance on nuclear power, such as disposal of toxic radioactive waste. Other issues include the increased thermal loading of aquatic systems and the possibility of radiation leaks. The economic, political, and greenhouse arguments overlook the much more serious implications of potential environmental catastrophes whose effects could persist for centuries. The narrow viewpoint focusing on the short-term gains inherent in increased reliance on nuclear energy overlooks the long-term, potentially devastating consequences of a nuclear-focused energy policy</p>', '<p>The passage refers to each of the following as risks involved in an increased reliance on nuclear power EXCEPT</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ17', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  All of the relevant risks are listed in the final paragraph.  This key paragraph lists four dangers, including those that are restated in (A), (B), and (D).  That leaves only two choices, one of which is very similar to part of the following sentence: “potential environmental catastrophes whose effects could persist for centuries.”  That is reflected in choice (E), leaving (C) as the one option that is not referred to as risk.</p>', 1001),
(1672, 0, 950347, 'Verbal', '<p>A shift towards increased reliance on nuclear energy in 21st-century America has intrigued many energy policy makers ever since the threat of diminishing fossil fuel reserves became apparent. Despite the drawbacks, some energy specialists endorse the idea, finding a hidden benefit in the fact that nuclear power plants cause no increase in greenhouse gas emissions. Others, however, contend that these are merely ancillary factors when the overall effects of increased nuclear power generation on the environment are considered. This alternative outlook concludes that the nuclear perspective, by focusing solely on decreases in fossil fuel reliance and greenhouse emissions, is based on the evaluation of only trivial considerations. This anti-nuclear view is currently the prevailing one, emphasizing the many negative environmental consequences of an increased reliance on nuclear energy.The central reasons for renewed interest in nuclear power plants come from entirely different considerations. Because the U.S. imports over 50 percent of its oil from foreign nations, including many in the Middle East, experts claim that an increased reliance on nuclear power would both bestow financial benefits on the national economy and advance the nation’s goal of energy independence. Moreover, they point to the political benefits that would accrue if the U.S. was no longer forced to obtain its energy supply from nations with unstable or antagonistic regimes. Increased reliance on nuclear power, therefore, would improve both the financial and geopolitical status of the United States.Although correctly evaluating these factors, this analysis ignores the environmental implications of an increased reliance on nuclear power, such as disposal of toxic radioactive waste. Other issues include the increased thermal loading of aquatic systems and the possibility of radiation leaks. The economic, political, and greenhouse arguments overlook the much more serious implications of potential environmental catastrophes whose effects could persist for centuries. The narrow viewpoint focusing on the short-term gains inherent in increased reliance on nuclear energy overlooks the long-term, potentially devastating consequences of a nuclear-focused energy policy</p>', '<p>The passage is primarily concerned with</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ18', '<p>The correct answer is (D). The passage alternates between discussing the upside and downside of increased reliance on nuclear energy.  The correct choice here should reflect that.  We can quickly rule out (A) and (B) as both of these choices focus only on one side of the debate. Choice (C) is too broad in scope.  The issue of nuclear energy isn’t discussed as a case study in part of a larger debate; it is the entire subject matter of the passage.  (E) is also too broad.</p>', 1001),
(1673, 0, 281977, 'Verbal', '<p>A shift towards increased reliance on nuclear energy in 21st-century America has intrigued many energy policy makers ever since the threat of diminishing fossil fuel reserves became apparent. Despite the drawbacks, some energy specialists endorse the idea, finding a hidden benefit in the fact that nuclear power plants cause no increase in greenhouse gas emissions. Others, however, contend that these are merely ancillary factors when the overall effects of increased nuclear power generation on the environment are considered. This alternative outlook concludes that the nuclear perspective, by focusing solely on decreases in fossil fuel reliance and greenhouse emissions, is based on the evaluation of only trivial considerations. This anti-nuclear view is currently the prevailing one, emphasizing the many negative environmental consequences of an increased reliance on nuclear energy.The central reasons for renewed interest in nuclear power plants come from entirely different considerations. Because the U.S. imports over 50 percent of its oil from foreign nations, including many in the Middle East, experts claim that an increased reliance on nuclear power would both bestow financial benefits on the national economy and advance the nation’s goal of energy independence. Moreover, they point to the political benefits that would accrue if the U.S. was no longer forced to obtain its energy supply from nations with unstable or antagonistic regimes. Increased reliance on nuclear power, therefore, would improve both the financial and geopolitical status of the United States.Although correctly evaluating these factors, this analysis ignores the environmental implications of an increased reliance on nuclear power, such as disposal of toxic radioactive waste. Other issues include the increased thermal loading of aquatic systems and the possibility of radiation leaks. The economic, political, and greenhouse arguments overlook the much more serious implications of potential environmental catastrophes whose effects could persist for centuries. The narrow viewpoint focusing on the short-term gains inherent in increased reliance on nuclear energy overlooks the long-term, potentially devastating consequences of a nuclear-focused energy policy</p>', '<p>The “merely ancillary factors” refer to which of the following?</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ19', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  The sentence in question refers to the previous sentence: “. Despite the drawbacks, some energy specialists endorse the idea, finding a hidden benefit in the fact that nuclear power plants cause no increase in greenhouse gas emissions.”  In other words, “ancillary factors” refers to the fact that increasing reliance on nuclear energy does not increase emissions, as reliance on fossil fuels would.  The correct choice is (B), which corresponds to this specific reference in the passage.</p>', 1001),
(1674, 0, 320135, 'Verbal', '<p>Which sentence connects floriography to nationalism?</p>', '<p>The idea that flowers connote meaning, otherwise known as floriography, the language of flowers, can be found in many cultures in historical periods., While examples of this can traced back to Buddhist texts in which Buddha’s words manifest in flowers falling from the sky, the language of flowers received considerably more attention in the 19th century when the scientific practices of documenting, defining and illustrating entered the natural sciences., This led to the creation of several popular lexicons of flora, which not only defined these blossom-based exchanges, but also became a manifestation of imperial hubris as new territories were conquered and recently discovered exotic species added to the repertoires. , Because so many were willing to capitalize on the Victorian fetish for flowers, competing versions of the their meanings soon emerged, and like most practices governed by sentimentality, consistency was not the hallmark., These meanings also incorporated other religious and cultural symbols., For example, verbena, which stood for the Kingdom of God in the Christian tradition, also came to represent prosperity in a later era, implying the connection between material wealth and divine reward., .  While there are a few commonplace associations, such as red roses for love, interest in floriography has declined significantly., While special occasions such as weddings may encourage dilettantes to dabble in the art when choosing their bouquets, few are fluent in this obscure language.</p>', 6, 'Test4-Sec2-VQ20', '<p>This led to the creation of several popular lexicons of flora, which not only defined these blossom-based exchanges, but also became a manifestation of imperial hubris as new territories were conquered and recently discovered exotic species added to the repertoires. The third sentence is correct.  If finding new flowers becomes a source of national pride, then a connection between floriography and nationalism is made.</p>', 1001),
(1675, 0, 576821, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Residents of Kenya express growing concern over the apparently endless ______________ of refugees fleeing neighboring Somalia.</p>', 2, 'Test4-sec1-V14', '<p>Credited Answer(s):\n     deluge, hordes\nThe phrase “apparently endless” indicates that there is a large quantity of refugees, eliminating dearth and deficiency, both of which suggest a lack.  Articulation refers to speech and hoax to deception, so these do not apply.  The answers are deluge and hordes, both of which imply many.\n</p>', 1001),
(1676, 0, 451290, 'Verbal', '<p>Critic: Some historians claim that the people who built this ring of stones thousands of years ago in England were knowledgeable about celestial events. This is not the case. The historians base their claim on the fact that two of the stones in the ring form a line pointing directly to the position of the sun at sunrise at the spring equinox. However, there are so many stones in the ring that the chance of at least one pair pointing in a celestially significant direction is high. </p>', '<p>The critic’s conclusion is questionable because</p>', 4, 'Test4-Sec2-V14', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  The problem with the critic’s conclusion is that he goes too far in stating categorically that the builders of the ring were not informed about celestial matters. The undermining of evidence offered in support of a statement does not prove the opposite of that statement. Just because the historians may have based their claim on flawed evidence does not mean that the opposite of their claim is true. Choices (B), (C) and (D) are merely smokescreens designed to confuse you: none accurately describes the process by which the critic reached his conclusion. (E) may be true, but the critic’s conclusion is founded on a fallacy in the historians’ thinking, not on any pretense of superior historical or scientific knowledge.</p>', 1001),
(1677, 0, 663749, 'Quant', '', '<p>The point (0, 4) is on a circle with its center at the origin.  Which of the following points are also on the circle?</p>', 2, 'Test4-Sec2-Q20', '<p>The correct answers are (4, 0) and (0, -4).  A quick sketch will help to solve this.The radius of the circle is the distance from the origin (0, 0) to the point (0, 4).  Thus the radius is 4.Any point on the circle will also be 4 units away from the origin. Thus the points (4, 0) and (0, -4) lie on the circle.If you draw (or imagine) the square with the vertices (4, 4), (4, -4), (-4, -4), (-4, 4), then you will see that the points (5, 0), (-5, -5) lie outside that square and therefore outside the circle. The point (-4, 4) is the vertex of the square and thus it is outside the circle as well.</p>', 1001),
(1678, 3, 156461, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Many members viewed her adherence to formal parliamentary procedure during the  meeting as (i)______________ ;  however, the founder of the organization greatly appreciated the (ii) ______________ her methods allowed and the unquestionable benefit of (iii) ______________ to the stated agenda.</p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec1-V4', '<p>    Credited Answer(s):(i) dictatorial(ii) expediency(iii) fidelityThe use of “however” indicates that the second half of the sentence, which is positive, will contradict the first.  Therefore, the leadership style at the meeting is dictatorial. Because the second half is positive, expediency is the only possible choice.  Similarly, fidelity to the agenda would also be a benefit.</p>', 1001),
(1679, 2, 425056, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Mitchell offered to call a taxi for her; she declined.  Then he offered his umbrella; again she ______________.  He kept trying to befriend her but she remained ______________.</p>', 3, 'Test4-Sec6-V5', '<p>Credited Answer(s):(i)  demurred        (ii)  aloofMitchell is not too successful in his attempts with the woman, who demurred, or showed reluctance, to his offer.  She remains distant, aloof.</p>', 1001),
(1681, 0, 551921, 'Quant', '', '<p>What is the length of the diagonal dotted line from points A to G in the rectangular solid above?</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep/uploads/1533641288.jpg"/></p>', 1, 'Test5-Sec1-Q1', '<p>To solve this question you have to figure out the distance from E to G. If EH is 3 and HG is 4, then EG must be 5 as in a 3-4-5 triangle. If AE is 5 (because CG is 5), then the triangle AEG is a right isosceles triangle with EG and AE both 5. You can calculate AG by taking the leg of the isosceles right triangle and multiplying by ?2 to get 5?2.The correct answer is choice (C).</p>', 1001),
(1682, 0, 150148, 'Quant', '', '<p>85 college graduates were asked if they ever took Russian Literature or European History.  14 students said they took both classes.  16 said they took neither class.Quantity A: The number who took Russian Literature onlyQuantity B: The number who took European History only</p>', 1, 'Test5-Sec1-Q2', '<p>The correct answer is (D). Of the 85 students surveyed, a total of 85 – 16 = 69 took the two classes. 14 took both, leaving 69 – 14 = 55 who took either Russian Literature only or European History only.  Without more information, we cannot determine how many took Russian Literature only and how many took European History only. The relationship cannot be determined with the given information.</p>', 1001),
(1683, 0, 556669, 'Quant', '', '<p>The below graph lists the number of cars sold per month at a car dealership from January (Jan) through June (Jun).  How many cars did the dealership sell on average, per month from January through the end of June?</p><p><img src="http://localhost/services/softprep//uploads/1533643312.jpg"/><br/></p><p><br/></p><p><br/></p>', 1, 'Test5-Sec1-Q3', '<p>According to the graph above, monthly sales were 2, 3, 5, 6, 9 and 8.  The sum of these numbers is 33.  Dividing by 6 to get the average sales per month, we get 33/6, or 11/2, which is 5.5. The correct answer is choice (E).</p>', 1001);
INSERT INTO `tbl_question_new` (`id`, `noofblanks`, `trackid`, `category`, `paragraph`, `name`, `question_type_id`, `note`, `solution`, `status`) VALUES
(1684, 0, 614186, 'Quant', '', '<p>The figure below shows three tangent circles (they touch at exactly one point), each with their centers along the same horizontal axis. The biggest circle contains two smaller ones. Of the two smaller circles, the larger one has a radius of 6 inches and the smaller one has a radius of 3 inches. What is the radius of the largest circle (in inches)?</p><p><img src="http://localhost/services/softprep//uploads/1533644099.jpg"/><br/></p>', 1, 'Test5-Sec1-Q4', '<p> Tangent circles are circles that touch each other, but do not overlap, nor do they leave any gaps between them. If the larger circle has a radius of 6 and the small one a radius of 3, we can calculate the diameter of each as 12 and 6. The diameter of the largest circle, then, would be 18. To find the radius, divide the diameter by 2: 18 / 2 = 9. The correct answer is C.</p>', 1001),
(1685, 0, 238502, 'Quant', '', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">x &gt; 0</span></p>\n<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Quantity A:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\n<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">&nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">x² + 1&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span>x³ + 1</span><br></span></p>', 1, 'Test5-Sec1-Q5', '<p>    The correct answer is (D).  In order to compare the two values, subtract 1 from each expression;  we are now comparing x² to x³. Dividing by x² will NOT change the sign of the comparison, because we know that it is a positive value (it cannot equal 0, because x is positive). So we are now comparing 1 to x.For values of x greater than 1, Quantity B will be greater.  But when x = 1, the two quantities are equal, and when x is less than 1, Quantity B will be smaller than Quantity A. Therefore the correct answer is D.</p>', 1001),
(1686, 0, 205692, 'Quant', '', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">A square garden plot with a diagonal of length 24√2 feet is surrounded by a concrete walkway that is 4 feet wide.</span></p>\n<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Quantity A:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\n<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">The area of the garden plot&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span>&nbsp;The area of the walkway</span><br></span></p>', 1, 'Test5-Sec1-Q6', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  Begin the solution by drawing a sketch of the garden and walkway that surrounds it.The square garden plot, when split by its diagonal, is cut into two 45-45-90 triangles.  The ratio of the three sides of a 45-45-90 triangle is x : x : x?2.  Thus, the diagonal of 24?2  tells us that the sides of the square are 24.  The area of the square garden plot is (24)(24) = 576 square feet.To calculate the area of the walkway we deduct the area of the garden plot from the area of the square formed by the outer edges of the walkway. That largest square will have the sides of (4 + 24 + 4) = 32 feet. Its area will be (32)(32) = 1024 square feet. So the area of the walkway is 1024 – 576 = 448 square feet.Therefore, the area of the square garden plot (576) is greater than the area of the concrete walkway (448). Quantity A is greater.</p>', 1001),
(1687, 0, 443104, 'Quant', '', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">3x + 2y = 10 and 5x – 3y = 23</span></p>\n<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Quantity A:&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B:&nbsp;</span></span></p>\n<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">x&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</span>y</span><!--EndFragment--></span></p>', 1, 'Test5-Sec1-Q7', '<p>The correct answer is (A).We must manipulate the two given equations in order to solve this problem.  Let\'s multiply the first equation by 3 to get 9x + 6y = 30.  Now multiply the second equation by 2 to get 10x – 6y = 46.  Now, if we add these two new equations together, the y terms will cancel out, and we get  19x = 76.  Solving for x yields x = 4.  Substituting this value into either of the original equations yields a y-value of -1.  Quantity A (4) is greater than Quantity B (-1).</p>', 1001),
(1688, 1, 117482, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Though the situation was initially stabilized in the capital after the unusual flooding, matters began to ______________ after days without power and clean water.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec1_v1', '<p>Credited Answer:  deteriorateWhen something deteriorates, it becomes progressively worse, which reasonably describes the conditions in a city after a disaster.  A clue to the proper word is the contrast with the earlier conditions, which had been stabilized.</p>', 1001),
(1689, 1, 984133, 'Verbal', '', '<p>After an injury to a marketing booth employee in 1999, the convention center started to ______________ the need for safety in the increasingly elaborate display designs.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec1_V2', '<p>Credited Answer:  underscoreAfter an accident, it is reasonable to expect the convention center to emphasize the need for safety, and not just record, tax, or dismiss it.  Underscore means to underline, or emphasize, and is the best fit.</p>', 1001),
(1690, 2, 231813, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Many critics consider late eighteenth century opera conventional and ______________.  Only when Mozart added dramatic elements to outstanding music did opera once again become ______________.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec1_v3', '<p>Credited Answers:(i)  insipid(ii)  enthralling</p>', 1001),
(1691, 2, 218190, 'Verbal', '', '<p>&#34;Those lectures have the most ______________ effect,&#34; she said.  &#34;Start explaining the ______________ of the powers wielded by the field offices of the National Labor Relations Board and I will be asleep in seconds.&#34;</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec1_v4', '<p>Credited Answers:(i)  soporific(ii)  minutiaeSomething that is soporific induces drowsiness, which is clearly the case here.  Often hearing the fine details, or minutiae, of a dull subject is too much for a tired mind.</p>', 1001),
(1692, 2, 707226, 'Verbal', '', '<p>The Senator\'s spokesman asserted that the Senator did not ______________ when explaining his ties to several figures lately indicted for insider trading.  The Senator, said the spokesman, was merely trying to ______________ himself from any unethical individuals.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec1_v5', '<p>Credited Answers:(i)  equivocate(ii)  dissociateThe context shows the spokesman defending the Senator\'s comments.  To equivocate means to conceal something with ambiguous language, which fits best here.  A Senator would want to distance himself from criminals, or dissociate himself from them.</p>', 1001),
(1693, 3, 922082, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Although well-known for the liberation of both women and minorities, the 1920s also correspond to a widespread (i) ______________ of the Ku Klux Klan, and a more (ii) ______________ white supremacist dialogue that displayed increasing (iii) ______________ toward newly visible immigrant populations.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec1_v6', '<p>Credited Answers:(i) resurrection(ii) comprehensive(iii) bigotryThe second half of the sentence must go against the first, which describes advancements of women and minorities; therefore, the racist Klan must have undergone a resurrection. The fact that it needed to encompass “supremacy” over new groups suggests the dialogue became more comprehensive.  Because the Klan perpetuates white supremacy, bigotry is what this dialogue would display.</p>', 1001),
(1694, 0, 282173, 'Verbal', '<p>Subprime, adjustable-rate mortgages, issued only to homeowners with poor credit histories, accounted for less than 15 percent of all mortgage loans in the city last year. However, they were the source of half of all foreclosures.</p>', '<p>Which of the following can be correctly inferred from the passage above?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec1_v7', '<p>Credited Answer: EThe correct answer is (E). This question asks you to infer information from the passage. Choice (E) is the only statement that can be logically derived from the passage: since subprime, adjustable-rate mortgages are issued to homeowners with poor credit history, and since subprime, adjustable-rate mortgages were the source of half of all foreclosures in the past year, then it must be true that half of all foreclosures in the past year were on the holders of subprime, adjustable-rate mortgages – or consumers with poor credit history. Choices (A) and (C) draw on unsupported assumptions. Choice (B) is unsupported by the passage: the passage talks about mortgage loans, not all loans.  Choice (D) makes a statement about a change over time, but the passage only discusses one year. Choice (E) must be true, and is the best answer.</p>', 1001),
(1695, 0, 528429, 'Verbal', '<p>Like many of the sciences, medicine has historically seen extended periods without significant technological advancement.  In the early modern period, there were very few modifications in medical practices. Therefore, medical care did not necessarily prolong the life expectancy of the patient, and remedies tended to be as deadly as the ailment.  However, this changed dramatically in the nineteenth century when post-Enlightenment scientific standards entered the discipline. This meant that medical schools and practitioners were more willing to engage in dissecting human bodies, a practice that was taboo because of the belief that desecration of the dead had implications for the afterlife.  The rise of science did not eradicate this superstition among the masses; therefore, grave robbing became a lucrative industry, paving the way for medical advancement.In spite of some of the ethically problematic aspects of medical study, this attention to physiology laid the groundwork for essential developments, such as Alexander Fleming’s quest for a non-toxic antibiotic, resulting in penicillin.  Similarly, Joseph Lister’s attention to the issues of sepsis spawned antiseptic procedures that greatly diminished a patient’s vulnerability to post-surgical infection.  Not only did this greatly enhance survival rates, but it also encouraged surgeons to attempt more adventurous surgeries, fostering other medical advances. Once medical practices encompassed effective scientific methodologies, innovative practitioners were able to continually build on each other’s success.  The corresponding improvement in literacy and mass communication also helped ensure that medical progress was documented and dispersed throughout the field.</p>', '<p>According to the passage, what rejuvenated the medical discipline?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec1_v8', '<p>The correct answer is (C). The passages clearly states that post-Enlightenment scientific standards allowed for advancement.  While distinguished practitioners and higher patient survival rates are discussed, these are the effects, not the causes.  Bacterial infections are not mentioned specifically, nor is a middle class.</p>', 1001),
(1696, 0, 804108, 'Verbal', '<p>Like many of the sciences, medicine has historically seen extended periods without significant technological advancement.  In the early modern period, there were very few modifications in medical practices. Therefore, medical care did not necessarily prolong the life expectancy of the patient, and remedies tended to be as deadly as the ailment.  However, this changed dramatically in the nineteenth century when post-Enlightenment scientific standards entered the discipline. This meant that medical schools and practitioners were more willing to engage in dissecting human bodies, a practice that was taboo because of the belief that desecration of the dead had implications for the afterlife.  The rise of science did not eradicate this superstition among the masses; therefore, grave robbing became a lucrative industry, paving the way for medical advancement.In spite of some of the ethically problematic aspects of medical study, this attention to physiology laid the groundwork for essential developments, such as Alexander Fleming’s quest for a non-toxic antibiotic, resulting in penicillin.  Similarly, Joseph Lister’s attention to the issues of sepsis spawned antiseptic procedures that greatly diminished a patient’s vulnerability to post-surgical infection.  Not only did this greatly enhance survival rates, but it also encouraged surgeons to attempt more adventurous surgeries, fostering other medical advances. Once medical practices encompassed effective scientific methodologies, innovative practitioners were able to continually build on each other’s success.  The corresponding improvement in literacy and mass communication also helped ensure that medical progress was documented and dispersed throughout the field.</p>', '<p>According to the passage, which of the following accelerated the spread of better medical practices?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec1_v9', '<p>The correct answer is (A). The final statement in the passage explains that better communication ensured that scientific advances were spread.  The passage is about change, not longstanding practices, and the advancement that cures all infections has yet to occur.  There is no mention of patients\' habits or whether or not Fleming taught anyone.</p>', 1001),
(1697, 0, 567641, 'Verbal', '<p>Like many of the sciences, medicine has historically seen extended periods without significant technological advancement.  In the early modern period, there were very few modifications in medical practices. Therefore, medical care did not necessarily prolong the life expectancy of the patient, and remedies tended to be as deadly as the ailment.  However, this changed dramatically in the nineteenth century when post-Enlightenment scientific standards entered the discipline. This meant that medical schools and practitioners were more willing to engage in dissecting human bodies, a practice that was taboo because of the belief that desecration of the dead had implications for the afterlife.  The rise of science did not eradicate this superstition among the masses; therefore, grave robbing became a lucrative industry, paving the way for medical advancement.In spite of some of the ethically problematic aspects of medical study, this attention to physiology laid the groundwork for essential developments, such as Alexander Fleming’s quest for a non-toxic antibiotic, resulting in penicillin.  Similarly, Joseph Lister’s attention to the issues of sepsis spawned antiseptic procedures that greatly diminished a patient’s vulnerability to post-surgical infection.  Not only did this greatly enhance survival rates, but it also encouraged surgeons to attempt more adventurous surgeries, fostering other medical advances. Once medical practices encompassed effective scientific methodologies, innovative practitioners were able to continually build on each other’s success.  The corresponding improvement in literacy and mass communication also helped ensure that medical progress was documented and dispersed throughout the field.</p>', '<p>Which of the following statements does the passage support?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec1_v10', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  The only statement supported by the passage is the one that indicates that cures were potentially deadly.  The passage does not say how available penicillin was or how literate doctors were in previous eras.  While the Enlightenment did apply to medicine, the passage does not say medicine was its focus.  While there was progress in surgical techniques, progress in the development of antibiotics is also mentioned.</p>', 1001),
(1698, 0, 161931, 'Verbal', '<p>Like many of the sciences, medicine has historically seen extended periods without significant technological advancement.  In the early modern period, there were very few modifications in medical practices. Therefore, medical care did not necessarily prolong the life expectancy of the patient, and remedies tended to be as deadly as the ailment.  However, this changed dramatically in the nineteenth century when post-Enlightenment scientific standards entered the discipline. This meant that medical schools and practitioners were more willing to engage in dissecting human bodies, a practice that was taboo because of the belief that desecration of the dead had implications for the afterlife.  The rise of science did not eradicate this superstition among the masses; therefore, grave robbing became a lucrative industry, paving the way for medical advancement.In spite of some of the ethically problematic aspects of medical study, this attention to physiology laid the groundwork for essential developments, such as Alexander Fleming’s quest for a non-toxic antibiotic, resulting in penicillin.  Similarly, Joseph Lister’s attention to the issues of sepsis spawned antiseptic procedures that greatly diminished a patient’s vulnerability to post-surgical infection.  Not only did this greatly enhance survival rates, but it also encouraged surgeons to attempt more adventurous surgeries, fostering other medical advances. Once medical practices encompassed effective scientific methodologies, innovative practitioners were able to continually build on each other’s success.  The corresponding improvement in literacy and mass communication also helped ensure that medical progress was documented and dispersed throughout the field.</p>', '<p>What practice is described in the passage that would weaken the credibility of those in the medical profession?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec1_v11', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  The passage explains that the study of human bodies and the dissection it required violated taboos about the treatment of dead bodies in this era.  Both the aggressive surgeries and new techniques saved lives, so these would not discredit doctors.  The limited opportunities to study the body partially caused the stagnation in the profession and the poor success rates for cures characterizes the previous era.</p>', 1001),
(1699, 0, 525290, 'Verbal', '', '<p>While the Plague of Athens, which occurred during the Peloponnesian Wars, has been documented as an early ______________ of the Black Plague, current research shows the cause was more likely typhus.</p>', 2, 'Test5_Sec1_v12', '<p>Credited Answer(s): epidemic , outbreak The sentence is about a plague that has occurred, not the symptoms it causes, and an antibody would work against the plague, which is not the case here.  Waning suggests a lessening, which does not apply, and disguise just does not make sense.  Therefore, the answers must be outbreak and epidemic, both of which relate to widespread disease.</p>', 1001),
(1700, 1, 541699, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Although she ______________ the fast-paced atmosphere and high-pressure aspects of her job, she elected to resign when her declining health began to impact her productivity.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec1_v13', '<p>The “Although” indicates that the two halves of the sentence must contradict each other.  If she had to resign, the first half of the sentence must say something positive about the situation, eliminating loathed.  Aspects of a job cannot be emphasized or contracted in the context of this sentence, which describes her feelings about the work. Regale means to entertain, so that does not make sense, leaving savored and relished as the best choices for describing her passion for the job.</p>', 1001),
(1701, 0, 752876, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Scientists in Manchester, England, have discovered that laser imaging technology can be used to recreate images of insects trapped in amber whose bodies have ______________.</p>', 2, 'Test5_Sec1_v14', '<p>The use of “recreate” suggests that something is missing, and the word describes a body that is no longer alive. With that in mind, evolved and advanced are quickly eliminated.  A body could rupture, but this sentence discusses fossilized remains, which would break, but not rupture. Encrusted does not work because something has to be encrusted, so “been” would have to precede the blank.  The answers are therefore decayed and deteriorated.</p>', 1001),
(1702, 0, 125136, 'Verbal', '', '<p>While analysts see General Motors\' recent commitment to expanding its Texas plant as an encouraging sign, they do not anticipate it will reinvigorate the ______________ manufacturing industry in the region.  </p>', 2, 'Test5_Sec1_v15', '<p>The “while” indicates that the second half of the sentence will contradict the first, so the second half of the sentence must be negative.  Therefore, the industry cannot be flourishing.  The word “reinvigorated” indicates that industry was there before, eliminating neophyte.  Sordid implies sleazy, which does not really apply to manufacturing, nor are industries generally described as contemporary in this context.  Therefore, defunct and obsolete, both implying the industry has vanished, are correct.</p>', 1001),
(1703, 0, 862596, 'Verbal', '<p>The judge told the criminal defendant, “You are consistently deceitful and cannot be trusted. Once you begin speaking honestly, I will begin believing you.” </p>', '<p>Which of the following is a central assumption on the part of the judge making this statement?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec1_v16', '<p>The correct answer is (C), which is the only assumption critical to the judge’s statement. The judge may well not believe (D) or (E) at all. She probably will assume (A) and (B), but, if she is mistaken, her statement remains valid even if the defendant ends up telling the truth only by accident, or never. However, if the judge can’t unfailingly recognize the truth when she hears it, her statement is just empty rhetoric.</p>', 1001),
(1704, 0, 140905, 'Verbal', '<p>The Gemsbok Oryx gazelle, commonly referred to as simply “Oryx,” is a majestic large antelope with striking features that is native to southern Africa\'s arid or semi-arid open grassland, scrub, open woodland and desert. The Oryx have adapted well to the extreme climates of the Kalahari semi-desert and the Namib Desert.  While the Oryx\'s body temperature can rise to 113 degrees Fahrenheit, a temperature that would kill most mammals, Oryx have a network of blood vessels in their nose that serves as a cooling system to keep their brains from overheating. While the Oryx will drink occasionally from streams or waterholes, the Oryx can also survive for days or even weeks without drinking water. The Oryx get much of their water from feeding on grasses, forbs and melons which also have been adapted for the desert climate by storing water.  Since Oryx are desert adapted, they breed year-round.  Other mammals usually breed during the rainy season. The Oryx\'s main predators in Africa are lions, hyenas, and wild dogs, and these predators ensure that only about ten percent of Oryx calves make it to their first birthday.The introduction of the African Oryx into New Mexico illustrates the problems of introducing exotic species into new ecosystems. Fewer than 100 Oryx were introduced into the White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico between 1969 and 1977 by the New Mexico Department of Game and Fish. This was done in order to open up a new big game hunting opportunity in a region where few big game were available to hunt. The Oryx\'s adaptations to harsh desert conditions in Africa have allowed them to be extremely successful in the arid, but less-harsh conditions of the Chihuahuan desert of New Mexico. In New Mexico, they have more rivers for hydration, as well as the desert plants of the southwest, such as yucca, buffalo gourds, and tumbleweeds. Further, the Oryx have no natural predators in the American southwest, as mountain lions and coyotes proved no match for the African Oryx. While it was originally estimated by scientists that the Oryx population would grow to only about 500 to 600 and remain in the Tularosa basin, by 2007 there were roughly 5,000 Oryx, and they have now spread to both the San Andreas and Sacramento Mountains.The spread of the Oryx outside of the White Sands Missile Range has caused concern to farmers, park service employees, biologists, and environmentalists because of overgrazing on farmlands and damage to the fragile desert habitat that is preserved in the White Sands National Monument. To keep the Oryx out of the White Sands National Monument, the National Park Service erected over 60 miles of fencing. There is a general consensus that the Oryx population of New Mexico needs to be greatly reduced and that Oryx should be kept within the White Sands Missile Range, though there are disagreements as to whether this should be achieved through shooting the animals, contraception, or other means. Many feel that the Oryx simply never should have been brought to New Mexico.</p>', '<p>Oryx get hydration from all of the following, except</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec1_v17', '<p>The correct answer is (D). The blood vessels in the nose of the Oryx help with cooling, not hydration. (A), (B), and (C) are all mentioned in the first paragraph as hydration sources for Oryx in Africa. Tumbleweeds are mentioned in paragraph three as a hydration source for Oryx living in New Mexico.</p>', 1001),
