roved no match for the African Oryx. While it was originally estimated by scientists that the Oryx population would grow to only about 500 to 600 and remain in the Tularosa basin, by 2007 there were roughly 5,000 Oryx, and they have now spread to both the San Andreas and Sacramento Mountains.The spread of the Oryx outside of the White Sands Missile Range has caused concern to farmers, park service employees, biologists, and environmentalists because of overgrazing on farmlands and damage to the fragile desert habitat that is preserved in the White Sands National Monument. To keep the Oryx out of the White Sands National Monument, the National Park Service erected over 60 miles of fencing. There is a general consensus that the Oryx population of New Mexico needs to be greatly reduced and that Oryx should be kept within the White Sands Missile Range, though there are disagreements as to whether this should be achieved through shooting the animals, contraception, or other means. Many feel that the Oryx simply never should have been brought to New Mexico.</p>', '<p>The passage suggests that, all of the following factors led to the Oryx\'s surviving in the Chihuahuan Desert, except</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec1_v19', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  As there are no lions or hyenas in the United States, the Oryx\'s distinctive markings are of no help to its survival in the Chihuahuan desert. (A), (C), (D), and (E) are all true, and are discussed in the first paragraph.</p>', 1001),
(1707, 0, 459888, 'Verbal', '<p>A national government plans to purchase a new earthquake warning system with revolutionary digital technology and features such as alarms, color-coded battery alerts, and an acoustic SOS signal. One aspect of the plan is that, in exchange for government research funding, security companies wanting to market this system to corporations must provide these additional features at no extra cost to buyers.</p>', '<p>Which of the following, if true, would point to a possible flaw in the government\'s plan?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec1_v20', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  If security companies can simply raise the price of the system so that they receive the same amount of money as they would have by offering the features as optional extras, the government hasn’t achieved anything on behalf of the corporations they sought to aid. Choice (B) is irrelevant, as the scope of the argument is limited to the companies that receive government funding and sell systems to corporations.  Choice (C) is incorrect since the argument is about funding, features, and prices, not the relative effectiveness of various entities when an earthquake is likely to occur.  If “some” were replaced by “all,” Choice (D) would be a good option, as it would indicate that the plan is redundant.  However, merely knowing that some companies already offer the features leaves open the possibility that the plan could induce some additional companies to do so. Choice (E) states that corporations do have a demand for these features, so it strengthens the rationale for the plan.</p>', 1001),
(1708, 1, 569749, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Councilman Fulton’s 2009 address at the ______________ Celebration highlighted Oregon\'s unique history since its 1859 admission to  the Union.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec2_v1', '<p>Credited Answer:  SesquicentennialFrom 1859 to 2009 is 150 years.  A celebration marking the passage of that time is a sesquicentennial.</p>', 1001),
(1709, 1, 371007, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Though Mills admitted telling the occasional inappropriate joke, and was a member of a men\'s club that some described as chauvinistic, he stated that he deeply resented the charge of being a ______________ and thought it a gross mischaracterization.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec2_v2', '<p>All the words fit the idea of a charge one would wish to deny, but only misogynist (a man who hates women) ties into the male/female theme in the sentence.</p>', 1001),
(1710, 2, 747159, 'Verbal', '', '<p>The Duke, however, was quite surprised at the reaction of his tenants.  Instead of ______________ compliance to his desire of extending his garden into the commons, he met ______________ resistance which took the form of innumerable delays and constant grumbling.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec2_v3', '<p>Credited Answer(s):(i)  obsequious(ii)  contumaciousAn obsequious tenant would be one who is obedient or servile.  That is contrasted here with a stubborn, or contumacious resistance (which was not violent or lacking self- control, or intemperate).</p>', 1001),
(1711, 3, 579071, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Although a poised and (i) ______________ speaker, (ii) ______________ hecklers got the best of him when the heated exchange rapidly deteriorated into a(n) (iii) ______________ of word salad on his part.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec2_v4', '<p>Credited Answer(s):(i)  eloquent(ii)  fractious(iii)  effusionThe “and” at the beginning of the phrase suggests the adjectives will be parallel, making eloquent the correct answer.  The adjective in the second blank describes the hecklers, who will be fractious, or unruly.  The fact that a word salad is a jumbled stream of words indicates that the answer must be effusion, or forceful flow.</p>', 1001),
(1712, 2, 557267, 'Verbal', '', '<p>Chairman Cohen cited the company\'s securing of ______________ title to major natural gas producing properties as a reason shareholders might expect future ______________.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec2_v5', '<p>Credited Answer(s):(i)  indefeasible(ii)  profitabilityIndefeasible means not able to be taken away.  A natural resources company would value having a firm legal hold of precious real estate.  Extraction of an energy resource, unencumbered by legal challenges, etc. might very well prove lucrative, or profitable.</p>', 1001),
(1713, 3, 567589, 'Verbal', '', '<p>While sailors and swimmers often receive (i) ______________ for their adventurous feats, such as swimming the English Channel or (ii) ______________ the globe by sailboat, the cases of those who do not triumph (iii) ______________ the marginal utility and great expense of such endeavors.</p>', 3, 'Test5_Sec2-V6', '<p>Credited Answer(s):(i)  acclaim(ii)  circumnavigating(iii)  accentuatesThe sentence discusses the kinds of activities that usually receive acclaim, or praise.  The use of the phrase “by sailboat” indicates that circumnavigating is the answer since it is the only choice that can be done in a boat.  When some fail, it would accentuate, or draw attention to, the disadvantages of this kind of endeavor.</p>', 1001),
(1715, 0, 800616, 'Verbal', '<p>The distinction that modern artists and art critics make between the arts, on the one hand, and crafts, on the other, was foreign to antiquity. Both arts and crafts were regarded by the ancient Greeks as “productions according to rule” and both were classified as techne, which can be translated “organized knowledge applied for producing a specific preconceived result.” This concept runs directly counter to the ingrained insight of modern aesthetic thought that art cannot be reduced to rule, cannot be produced in accordance with pre-established concepts, and cannot be evaluated using a set of rules reducible to a formula. The Greek concept, with its notion that the criterion for judging arts and crafts was the “perfection” of their production, was predominant until the 18th century, when the French aesthetician C. Baeux heralded the idea that what distinguishes the arts from the crafts and the sciences was the arts\' production of beauty. This idea lasted until the beginning of the 20th century when some critics argued that “beauty“ was a highly ambiguous term, far too broad for the purpose of defining or evaluating art, while, on the other hand, many artists expressly repudiated “beauty“ because of its too narrow associations with an outmoded view that art was beautiful and therefore should not be evaluated or analyzed, but should merely be appreciated.Since 1900, many definitions of art have emerged, each of them covering a sector of accepted creative and critical practice but none of them, apparently, are applicable to the whole of what is accepted as art by the art world. Not only do modern definitions of art fail to agree on any common approach, but individually many of them do not even serve to differentiate those works that are conventionally adopted as art by many artists and critics from those that are not. For example, the “mimetic” theory holds that art reproduces reality, but although amateurs\' photographs reproduce reality, most artists and art critics do not consider them art. Much of what is recognized as art conforms to the definition of art as the creation of forms, but an engineer and the illustrator of a geometry textbook also construct forms. The inadequacy of these definitions suggests a strong element of irrationality, for it suggests that the way in which artists and art critics think about works of art does not correspond with the way in which they actually distinguish those things that they recognize as art.</p>', '<p>The author is primarily concerned in the first paragraph with discussing</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2_v7', '<p>The correct answer is (E). In the first paragraph, the author begins by contrasting the definitions of art between modern artists, art critics and the classical philosophers. Then he goes on to elaborate upon the Greek concept of art. He then tells us how the French aesthetician Charles Baeux distinguished the arts from crafts. He concludes the paragraph by saying that since 1900 a large number of definitions of art have emerged. Hence, (E) is the correct answer. The answer is directly available from the first paragraph. Choice (A) is incorrect because, although the first paragraph does mention producing art, this is only a passing mention; additionally, there is no discussion of “problems” of producing art. Although he discusses the Greeks, the author never gives a criticism of Greek art (C). The author does state that both arts and crafts were regarded similarly by the Greeks, but he does not give specific similarities, thus Choice (D) is also incorrect.  Choice (B) is too broad to summarize the first paragraph.</p>', 1001),
