(1718, 0, 242153, 'Verbal', '<p>Researchers have discovered a female skull in Ethiopia that is reputed to be the oldest member of the human family tree. Ardipithecus ramidus, known as Ardi, whose remains date from 4 million years ago, is the common ancestor to whom all humans can trace their lineage. Ardi predates Lucy, presents a fuller picture of human evolution, and may even explain why humans began to walk upright – in pursuit of better reproductive opportunities, a hypothesis first proposed by Lovejoy in the 1980s.It was long thought that the development of bipedalism could be traced back to chimpanzees, or more specifically, to an “intermediate figure” bridging the evolutionary gap between chimpanzees and humans. Thus, most research into the origins of bipedalism focused on the similarities between chimpanzees and humans. Since the discovery of Ardi, however, scientists have stopped looking down that particular evolutionary path. Ardipithecus ramidus is neither chimp nor human; instead, her features appear to combine human traits with those found in ancient apes, which are related neither to chimpanzees nor to gorillas.Ardi’s pelvis, hands and feet are of particular interest to researchers. The structure of the bones suggests that she was adapted for bipedalism, but only while moving about the ground: in the trees, she moved like a quadruped, using both hands and feet to get from one place to another.  This makes Ardi unique among our known human ancestors.  Although some researchers have suggested that Ardipithecus ramidus is a relic of an unrelated and now-extinct species, the general conclusion is that Ardi is exactly what she appears to be: hard evidence of a link between the human species and the tree-dwellers who came before us.</p>', '<p>The passage suggests that the human family tree</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2_v10', '<p>The correct answer is (A). This question asks you to find information that is suggested by the passage.  Choice (A) correctly summarizes the information we are given in the first two sentences: “...the oldest member of the human family tree. Ardipithecus ramidus, whose remains date from 4 million years ago, is the common ancestor to whom all humans can trace their lineage.”Choice (B) is not supported because the passage does not explicitly exclude Lucy from the human family tree; all we know about Lucy is that Ardi “predates” her.Choice (C) is the opposite of what the passage implies: it tells us, to the contrary, that Ardipithecus ramidus is included in the human family tree, not just Homo sapiens.Choice (D) is incorrect because the passage implies that the current human family tree does not give us a complete picture of human evolution.</p>', 1001),
