age.  What was discovered in Ethiopia?  The first sentence tells us, “Researchers discovered a skull in Ethiopia that is reputed to be the oldest member of the human family tree”.  This supports choice (C), “The skull of a human ancestor”.  Choices (A), (B), (D), and (E) are not supported by the passage.</p>', 1001),
(1720, 0, 834372, 'Verbal', '<p>Researchers have discovered a female skull in Ethiopia that is reputed to be the oldest member of the human family tree. Ardipithecus ramidus, known as Ardi, whose remains date from 4 million years ago, is the common ancestor to whom all humans can trace their lineage. Ardi predates Lucy, presents a fuller picture of human evolution, and may even explain why humans began to walk upright – in pursuit of better reproductive opportunities, a hypothesis first proposed by Lovejoy in the 1980s.It was long thought that the development of bipedalism could be traced back to chimpanzees, or more specifically, to an “intermediate figure” bridging the evolutionary gap between chimpanzees and humans. Thus, most research into the origins of bipedalism focused on the similarities between chimpanzees and humans. Since the discovery of Ardi, however, scientists have stopped looking down that particular evolutionary path. Ardipithecus ramidus is neither chimp nor human; instead, her features appear to combine human traits with those found in ancient apes, which are related neither to chimpanzees nor to gorillas.Ardi’s pelvis, hands and feet are of particular interest to researchers. The structure of the bones suggests that she was adapted for bipedalism, but only while moving about the ground: in the trees, she moved like a quadruped, using both hands and feet to get from one place to another.  This makes Ardi unique among our known human ancestors.  Although some researchers have suggested that Ardipithecus ramidus is a relic of an unrelated and now-extinct species, the general conclusion is that Ardi is exactly what she appears to be: hard evidence of a link between the human species and the tree-dwellers who came before us.</p>', '<p>Which of the following, if true, would most strengthen the hypothesis mentioned in the final sentence of the first paragraph? </p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2_v12', '<p>The correct answer is (C). This question asks you to strengthen a hypothesis.  The hypothesis mentioned in the final sentence of the first paragraph is that humans began to walk upright in order to achieve better reproductive opportunities.  Choice (C) strengthens the hypothesis by drawing a link between bipedalism, or walking upright, and better reproductive opportunities: “Bipedal animals are able to seek out a wider variety of potential mates”.  Choices (A) and (D) are unrelated to the hypothesis.  Choice (B) tells us more about how Ardi’s bone structure facilitated walking, but it tells us nothing about the link between bipedalism and better reproductive opportunities.  Choice (E) directly contradicts a statement made earlier in the passage.  Choice (C) is the only answer that strengthens the hypothesis made in the final sentence of the first paragraph.</p>', 1001),
(1721, 0, 190017, 'Verbal', '<p>Research has shown that high levels of dietary protein can lead to cancer.  People who exercise regularly or who eat diets low in protein have lower levels of IGF-1, a hormone linked to the growth of cancerous tumors.  Therefore, in order to decrease your cancer risk, it is best to eliminate protein from your diet. </p>', '<p>Which of the following, if true, most seriously weakens the argument?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2_v13', '<p>The correct answer is (C), the statement which most seriously weakens the argument.  The fact that high levels of dietary protein can lead to cancer does not imply that protein should be eliminated entirely from the diet.  Instead, we may infer only that we should try to eat healthy amounts of protein.  Choice (C) tells us why: because dietary protein contains several essential amino acids, none of which is produced by the body.  If these amino acids are only available through dietary protein, then it cannot be true that we should eliminate protein entirely from our diets.  Choice (A) fails to weaken the argument.  The fact that foods high in protein are also high in fat is irrelevant to the argument; it merely supports the idea that a high-protein diet is not necessarily healthy.  Choice (B) strengthens the argument by supporting the notion that high levels of dietary protein (which is found in red meat) can lead to cancer.  Choice (D) has no effect on the argument.  The fact that diet and exercise together are more effective against cancer cannot tell us how much protein to ingest.  Choice (E) is irrelevant; the fact that protein is also found in plants might cast doubt on the practicality of eliminating protein entirely from a diet, but it does not tell us anything about whether eliminating</p>', 1001),
(1722, 0, 968148, 'Verbal', '<p>A company recently implemented a proposal to subsidize a physical fitness program for employees judged to have a 60% or higher chance of developing Type II diabetes. The CFO praised the plan, saying that it would reduce long term health care costs.</p>', '<p>The use of this proposal may not be effective as part of the company\'s plan to lower health-care costs if which of the following were true?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2-v14', '<p>The correct answer is (B).  The plan aims to lower health-care costs.  The main assumption made by the plan is that the physical fitness program will lower costs by preventing employees who are at risk of developing Type II diabetes from developing the disease. Choice (B) provides a way in which the program may fail to reduce health-care costs even if diabetes is reduced. Indeed, if (B) were true, the plan might result in higher health-care costs. Choice (A) is wrong because the use of the term “not all employees” leaves plenty of room for the plan to be successful. If it said “no employees” then it would seriously weaken the plan.  Choice (C) strengthens the argument, suggesting other ways in which the fitness program could reduce health-care costs.  Choice (D) is irrelevant, as the plan involves making the fitness program available to those who are judged to have a high risk, not those who are aware of their degree of risk. Choice (E) strengthens the argument, more or less confirming that the plan\'s goal will come to pass.</p>', 1001),
(1723, 0, 970970, 'Verbal', '<p>The increase in the number of news stories revealed to be false serves to strengthen the argument that the media company CEO prioritizes audience size over reporting the truth. In the past year, local TV stations have even set up teams to identify false stories. </p>', '<p>The argument assumes that: </p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2_v15', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  The conclusion makes sense only if we assume (A), that the media CEO is the one who decides what to air. If (A) weren’t true and this decision were up to someone other than the media CEO, the argument would fall apart. Any of the other answer choices could be true, but none follows inevitably from the passage.</p>', 1001),
(1724, 0, 441014, 'Verbal', '<p>The government recently approved the use of a blend of 15% ethanol and 85% gasoline for automotive use. Environmentalists approve of the mixture, because ethanol produces less pollution than gasoline when it burns. However, opponents of ethanol-based fuels claim that these fuels produce less energy per gallon than does gasoline.</p>', '<p>Which of the following, if true, most strongly supports an argument by opponents of ethanol-based fuels that the use of gasoline is more environmentally friendly than the use of ethanol fuels?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2_v16', '<p>The correct answer is (D). If ethanol is only slightly less polluting per gallon, but it takes many more gallons of ethanol to produce the same amount of energy, it is likely that using ethanol based-fuels will actually produce more pollution in the long run than using gasoline.  Choice (A) only addresses the cost of using ethanol. While this may be a consideration affecting the viability of using ethanol-based fuels, it does not affect the conclusion which the stem asks you to strengthen – that ethanol-based fuels are less environmentally friendly than gasoline. In Choice (B), the fact that ethanol produces a significant amount of pollution does not strengthen the conclusion that gasoline is more environmentally friendly, absent the knowledge of how this compares to the amount of pollution produced by gasoline. In fact, the stimulus has already indicated that whatever pollution ethanol produces is less than that produced by gasoline.  Choice (C) actually weakens the conclusion of the opponents of ethanol. If gasoline has other negative environmental effects, then it is less likely to be more environmentally friendly than ethanol.  Choice (E) appears to give a reason that ethanol may not be environmentally friendly. However, it merely states that “some” facilities (at least one) were built on these lands, and doesn’t necessarily mean that harm was done to the wildlife. Additionally, the location of the research facilities has no bearing on the comparison made regarding the actual use of these two kinds of fuels</p>', 1001),
(1725, 0, 791502, 'Verbal', '<p>Bioinformatics is the field of science in which biology, computer science, and information technology merge to form a single discipline. The ultimate goals of the field are to enable the discovery of new biological insights and to create a global perspective from which unifying principles in biology can be discerned. At the beginning of the “genomic revolution,” a bioinformatics concern was the creation and maintenance of a database to store biological information, such as nucleotide and amino acid sequences. Development of this type of database involved not only design issues, but also the development of complex interfaces whereby researchers could both access existing data and submit new or revised data.Ultimately, all of this information must form a comprehensive picture of normal cellular activities so that researchers may study how these activities are altered in different disease states. Therefore, the field of bioinformatics has evolved such that the most pressing task now involves the analysis of various types of data, including nucleotide and amino acid sequences, protein domains, and protein structures. The actual process of analyzing and interpreting data is referred to as computational biology. Important sub-disciplines within bioinformatics and computational biology include the development and implementation of tools that enable efficient access to, and use and management of, various types of information; and the development of new algorithms (mathematical formulas) and statistics with which to assess relationships among members of large data sets, such as methods to locate a gene within a sequence, predict protein structure and/or function, and cluster protein sequences into families of related sequences.Bioinformatics promises to lead to advances in understanding basic biological processes and, in turn, advances in the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of many genetic diseases. Bioinformatics has transformed the discipline of biology from a purely lab-based science into an information science as well. The implications behind this change, for both science and medicine, are staggering.</p>', '<p>The passage is primarily concerned with which of the following?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2_v17', '<p>The correct answer is (A). The passage details the origins and goals of the field of bioinformatics, and how this field is likely to lead to important advances in other fields of science and medicine. Choice (A) encompasses these ideas.  Choice (B) is incorrect because, while the author does describe some of the motivations for the development of bioinformatics, this answer choice is too specific. Choice (C) is also too specific, and only focuses on the content of the third paragraph; it is also too extreme as the author does not indicate that bioinformatics is one of the “most important” areas. Choice (D) misses that the passage also addresses the origins of bioinformatics. (E) is incorrect because the author does not discuss a particular method of research; and, while he does discuss the origins of bioinformatics, this misses his focus on the applications and implications of the field.</p>', 1001),
(1726, 0, 973344, 'Verbal', '<p>Bioinformatics is the field of science in which biology, computer science, and information technology merge to form a single discipline. The ultimate goals of the field are to enable the discovery of new biological insights and to create a global perspective from which unifying principles in biology can be discerned. At the beginning of the “genomic revolution,” a bioinformatics concern was the creation and maintenance of a database to store biological information, such as nucleotide and amino acid sequences. Development of this type of database involved not only design issues, but also the development of complex interfaces whereby researchers could both access existing data and submit new or revised data.Ultimately, all of this information must form a comprehensive picture of normal cellular activities so that researchers may study how these activities are altered in different disease states. Therefore, the field of bioinformatics has evolved such that the most pressing task now involves the analysis of various types of data, including nucleotide and amino acid sequences, protein domains, and protein structures. The actual process of analyzing and interpreting data is referred to as computational biology. Important sub-disciplines within bioinformatics and computational biology include the development and implementation of tools that enable efficient access to, and use and management of, various types of information; and the development of new algorithms (mathematical formulas) and statistics with which to assess relationships among members of large data sets, such as methods to locate a gene within a sequence, predict protein structure and/or function, and cluster protein sequences into families of related sequences.Bioinformatics promises to lead to advances in understanding basic biological processes and, in turn, advances in the diagnosis, treatment, and prevention of many genetic diseases. Bioinformatics has transformed the discipline of biology from a purely lab-based science into an information science as well. The implications behind this change, for both science and medicine, are staggering.</p>', '<p>The author implies that which of the following was a concern arising out of the “genomic revolution” that bioinformatics seeks to address?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2_v18', '<p>Choice (D) correctly addresses the motivation, given in the third sentence, for applying bioinformatics to genomics – “the creation and maintenance of a database to store biological information.”  Choice (A) is a detail that is given in the passage but is not given as a problem arising from the genomic revolution. Choice (B) details a requirement for the database to be developed, but allowing data revision was not the primary reason bioinformatics was used. Choice (C) is described as a sub-discipline of bioinformatics, but this is not linked in the passage to the genomic revolution. Choice (E) appears in the last paragraph as an area of future usefulness of bioinformatics, not an early application.</p>', 1001),
