ipline of biology from a purely lab-based science into an information science as well. The implications behind this change, for both science and medicine, are staggering.</p>', '<p>The passage is primarily concerned with which of the following?</p>', 4, 'Test5_Sec2-V6', '<p>The correct answer is (A). The passage details the origins and goals of the field of bioinformatics, and how this field is likely to lead to important advances in other fields of science and medicine. Choice (A) encompasses these ideas.  Choice (B) is incorrect because, while the author does describe some of the motivations for the development of bioinformatics, this answer choice is too specific. Choice (C) is also too specific, and only focuses on the content of the third paragraph; it is also too extreme as the author does not indicate that bioinformatics is one of the “most important” areas. Choice (D) misses that the passage also addresses the origins of bioinformatics. (E) is incorrect because the author does not discuss a particular method of research; and, while he does discuss the origins of bioinformatics, this misses his focus on the applications and implications of the field.</p>', 1001),
(1730, 0, 605990, 'Quant', '', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">x + y &gt; 3.</span></p><p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Quantity A:                            <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B: </span></span></p><p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">    <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">(x + y) / 3                               </span>3 / (x + y)</span><br/></span></p><!--EndFragment-->', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q8', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  Rather than using algebra, let\'s use logic to solve this problem.  Since x + y &gt; 3, Quantity A will have a numerator greater than 3 and a denominator equal to 3.  Thus, Quantity A\'s value will (always) be greater than 1.  Quantity B\'s numerator is 3, and its denominator will be greater than 3, so Quantity B\'s value will (always) be less than 1.  Therefore, Quantity A will always be greater.</p>', 1001),
(1731, 0, 605636, 'Quant', '', '<p>The sum of 5 consecutive integers is 105. What is the sum of the first 2 integers?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q9', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  Let x be designated the first integer.  The next consecutive integer after x is (x + 1), and the next one after that one is (x +2).  Continue this pattern and then set up the equation x + (x + 1) + (x + 2) + (x + 3) + (x + 4) = 105. This becomes (5x + 10) = 105.  Solve for x by subtracting 10 and then dividing by 5.  So x will equal 19, which is the value of the first integer.  The second integer will be 20, and their sum will be 39, choice (C).</p>', 1001),
(1732, 0, 486163, 'Quant', '', '<p>A prize of $600 is to be distributed among 20 winners, each of whom must be awarded at least $20. If 2/5 of the prize will be distributed to 3/5 of the winners, what is the greatest possible individual award?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q10', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  If 2/5 of the prize (2/5 of $600 = $240) is distributed to 3/5 of the winners (3/5 of 20 is 12 winners), this indicates that each of those 12 winners will receive the minimum of $20. That leaves $360 to be divided among 8 remaining winners. If 7 of those winners receive the minimum $20 (total $140), then the eighth winner would receive all the remaining prize money, $360 – $140 = $220.</p>', 1001),
(1733, 0, 151096, 'Quant', '', '<p>x # y  =  xy – y,  then 2 # 3 =</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q11', '<p>The correct answer is (B). The defined function specifies the following pattern:  multiply the first item (x) by the second item (y) and then subtract the second item (y).  Thus 2 # 3 requires that we multiply the first item (2) by the second item (3) and subtract the second item (3), which equals (2)(3) – 3  =  6 – 3 = 3, which is the choice B.</p>', 1001),
(1734, 0, 982662, 'Quant', '', '<p>What is the units digit of the sum of the first 30 terms of the sequence 5¹, 5², 5³, . . .?</p>', 5, 'Test5_Sec1_Q12', '<p>The answer is 0. Calculate the terms of the sequence:  5, 25, 125, 625, and you see a pattern with the units digits of these numbers. It is always 5. If there are even number of terms, the units digit of the sum will be 0. If there were odd number of terms, the units digit of the sum would be 5.We have 30 terms, so the units digit of the sum will be 0</p>', 1001),
(1735, 0, 900908, 'Quant', '', '<p>The distance around the curved part of a semicircle is 12 inches.  What is the area of the circle in square inches?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q13', '<p>Since half the circle has a circular distance of 12 inches, the entire circle will have a circumference of 24 inches.  Use the formula C = 2?r and substitute 24 for C, so 24 = 2?r.  Solving for r yields 12/? = r.Now let\'s find the area of the circle, using A = ?r².  We get A = ? (12/?)², or A = ?(144/?²) which simplifies to A = 144/?</p>', 1001),
(1736, 0, 111523, 'Quant', '', '<p>The chart shows the number of coins that a woman has in her wallet. What fraction of the total value of the money is the value of the nickels, in cents?</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1533728842.jpg"/><br/></p>', 5, 'Test5_Sec1_Q14', '<p>The correct answer is 25/113.  To find the total value in coins, multiply the number of each coin by its value.  26(0.01) + 10(0.05) + 5(0.10) + 4(0.25) = 0.26 + 0.50 + 0.50 + 1.00 = 2.26, which is 226 cents.  The value of the nickels is 10(0.05) = 0.5, or 50 cents.  The fraction of nickels, then, will be 50/226 which reduces to 25/113.</p>', 1001),
(1737, 0, 516235, 'Verbal', '', '<p>The chart shows the number of coins that a woman has in her wallet. The woman randomly draws two consecutive coins from the wallet without replacement.  Assume that all coins are equally likely to be drawn.  What is the probability that the first coin drawn is a quarter and the second is a nickel?  Round your answer to two decimal places.</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1533728855.jpg"/><br/></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q15', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  To begin, find the total number of coins in the wallet.  26 + 10 + 5 + 4 = 45.  The probability that the first coin drawn is a quarter is 4/45.  Without replacing the quarter, there are now 44 coins in the purse, so the probability that the second coin drawn is a nickel is 10/44.  Multiply the probabilities.  (4/45)(10/44) = 40/1980 ? 0.02, choice (A).</p>', 1001),
(1738, 0, 737255, 'Quant', '', '<p>Tim traveled 40 percent of the distance of his trip alone, went another 20 miles with Sam, and then finished the last half of the trip alone. How many miles long was the trip?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q16', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  Think of the trip as having three parts: alone (40%), with Sam (20 mi.) , and alone again (50%). In order for the trip percentage to add to 100%, the part of the trip with Sam must constitute 10% of the trip, and this is 20 miles.  To evaluate the entire length of the trip, multiply 10% by 10 to get 100%, and, similarly, multiply 20 miles by 10 to get the entire trip, which is 200 miles, choice (D).</p>', 1001),
(1739, 0, 745221, 'Quant', '', '<p>You put 4 red-painted circles, each with diameter 4 inches, inside a black square with sides 8 inches.  The circles touch but do not overlap.  How much black space is visible after the red circles are placed in the square?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q17', '<p>First, find the area of the black square.  A = s², so A = 64.Now find the area of the four circles.  One circle has A = ?r², or A = ?(2)², or 4?.  There are four circles, so the area of the four circles is 16?.</p>', 1001),
(1740, 0, 472783, 'Quant', '', '<p>The price of oil decreased from $60 per barrel to $54 per barrel.  By what percent did the price decrease?</p>', 5, 'Test5_Sec1_Q18', '<p>The correct answer is 10.  Percent change = [(difference)/(starting value)] × 100%.  For this problem, percent decrease = 6/60 × 100% = .10 × 100% = 10%.</p>', 1001),
(1741, 0, 462663, 'Quant', '', '<p>Given the two lists:List 1: 7, 8, 12, 15  List 2: 2, 10, 10, 13, 18</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q19', '<p>Mean (average) – sum of all elements of a set divided by the number of the elements.Median – if the number of the elements in a set is odd, then it is the middle number of the set arranged in ascending or descending order;if the number of the elements in the set is even, then it is the average of the two numbers in the middle of the arranged set.Mode – the element(s) that appears most frequently.Range – The largest element minus the smallest.Let\'s look at each choice.Choice A:  the mean of List 1 is 42/4 = 10.5, and the mean of List 2 is 53/5 = 10.6.  False Choice B:  The median of List 1 is (8 + 12)/2 = 10, and the mode of List 2 is 10. FalseChoice C:  It is not necessary to calculate the standard deviation.  Just note that the data are much more spread about List 2, so its standard deviation is greater.  FalseChoice D:  The range of List 1 is (15 – 7) = 8 and the range of List 2 = (18 – 2) = 16 .  False.All of the first 4 answer choices are false.  Therefore, Choice E, none of these is true, is correct.</p>', 1001),
(1742, 0, 451384, 'Quant', '', '<p>What is the angle between the clock hands when it is 1:50?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec1_Q20', '<p>A circle has 360 degrees.  The clock has 12 divisions;  hence, each division is 30 degrees.  The minute hand is on 10 when it is 1:50, and the hour hand is somewhere between 1 and 2.The exact number of degrees between 1 and 2 is determined as follows:  because the clock has advanced 50 minutes since 1 o’clock, the hour hand is 50/60 (or 5/6) of the way between 1:00 and 2:00.  There are 30 degrees between 1 and 2, so at 1:50, the hour hand will be (5/6 × 30) = 25 degrees beyond 1.The final answer will be:  between 10:00 and 1:00 is (3 × 30) = 90 degrees; add to this the 25 degrees that the hour hand has progressed between 1 and 2, and the final answer is 115 degrees, choice (D).</p>', 1001),
(1743, 0, 344247, 'Quant', '', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">A coin is flipped and a fair 6-sided die is rolled.</span></p><p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">    Quantity A:                                  <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B:</span></span></p><p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;"> <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">The probability of getting               <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">0.08</span><!--EndFragment--><br/></span></span></span><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">  a head and a 5</span></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q1', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  These are two independent events, so their probabilities will be multiplied.  The probability of getting a head is 1/2 or 0.5.  The probability of rolling a 5 is 1/6.  Multiply these:  (1/2)(1/6) = 1/12 ? 0.083.  Since 0.083 is greater than 0.08, Quantity A is greater</p>', 1001),
(1744, 0, 340912, 'Quant', '', '<p>w &lt; x &lt; y &lt; z<br/>Quantity A:                     <span style="color: rgb(103, 106, 108);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B:</span></p><p><span style="color: rgb(103, 106, 108);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">  <span style="color: rgb(103, 106, 108);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">wx                                        </span>yz</span><!--EndFragment--><br/><br/></p><p><br/><br/></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q2', '<p>The key to solving this problem is in the selection of sample values for the four variables.  If all of them were positive integers, for example 2, 3, 4, and 5, it is obvious that Quantity B would be larger.But if we were to let w and x be negative (such as -2 and -1, respectively), and let y = 0 and z be 2, then Quantity A would be larger, because wx would be +2 and yz would be 0.When this kind of inconsistency happens in the choice of the greater quantity, the correct answer is (D), the relationship cannot be determined from the information given.</p>', 1001),
(1745, 0, 965692, 'Quant', '', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">Quantity A:                       <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B: </span></span></p><p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">  <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">(?20)/2</span>                                    5/?5</span><!--EndFragment--><br/><br/></span></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q3', '<p>The correct answer is (C). Let\'s simplify each of the quantities and then compare them.(?20)/2 can be simplified as ?[(4)(5)] / 2.  Simplifying the numerator yields (2?5)/2.  Cancel the 2s to get ?5 as the simplified version of Quantity A.Quantity B can be simplified by writing the number 5 as the product of its square roots:  5 = (?5)(?5).  Quantity B can then be written as [(?5)(?5)] / ?5.  By cancellation, Quantity B becomes ?5.  Comparing the two quantities we see that they are equal, choice (C)</p>', 1001),
(1746, 0, 284207, 'Quant', '', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">                  Quantity A:                                                <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);float: none;">Quantity B: </span><br/></span><span style="background-color: transparent;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">(The value of the area of the circle)/                               1</span></p><p><span style="background-color: transparent;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">(the value of the circumference of the circle)</span><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"><br/></span></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q4', '<p>The correct answer is (C).  The value of the area of the circle, using A = ?r², is A = ?(2)² = 4?.  The value of the circumference of the circle, using C = 2?r, is C = 2?(2) = 4?.  The fraction in Quantity A becomes 4?/4? = 1.  This is the same value as Quantity B, so they are equal, choice (C).</p>', 1001),
(1747, 0, 180124, 'Quant', '', '<p><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;">         Quantity A:                      <span style="background-color: transparent;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"><span class="Apple-tab-span">           </span></span><span style="background-color: transparent;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Quantity B: </span><br/></span><span style="background-color: transparent;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">The remainder when                               1</span></p><p><span style="background-color: transparent;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"> x is divided by 2</span><span style="color: #000000;background-color: transparent;"></span></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q6', '<p>The correct answer is (B). Division by 2 is quite simple. If a dividend is even, then the remainder is 0. If a dividend is odd, then the remainder is 1. So the question statement implies that (x + 5) is odd and therefore x is even. The remainder when even x is divided by 2 is 0. Quantity B is greater.</p>', 1001),
(1748, 0, 252175, 'Quant', '', '<p>If the point (2, -6) is the center of a circle and the point (2, 3) is on the circle, what is the circumference of the circle?</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1533728906.jpg"/><br/></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q7', '<p>(A) Point O is the center of the circle therefore OC is the radius. Point O lies on the line segment AB so AB is the diameter. Any diameter is twice a radius, so the answer is 10 × 2 = 20 inches, choice (A).</p>', 1001),
(1749, 0, 353617, 'Quant', '', '<p>-3 is a solution of the equation bx² + 2x + 4 = 0, where b is a fixed number. What is the value of b?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q9', '<p>The correct answer is (C). If x = -3 is a solution then we can plug it in and get the equality b(-3)² + 2(-3) + 4 = 0, which is the equation for b. Therefore b = 2/9. The answer is C.</p>', 1001),
(1750, 0, 174501, 'Quant', '', '<p>The area of a right triangle is 10 square inches.  If the length of each leg is a positive integer, then what are possible values for the length of the hypotenuse, in inches?  </p>', 2, 'Test5_Sec2_Q10', '<p>The correct answers are ?41, ?104, and ?401.The area of a right triangle is A = 1/2 (base)(height).  Substitute the known  value for the area:  10 = (1/2)(b)(h), which becomes 20 = (b)(h).  Both b and h are positive integers, so their possible values are (1 and 20), (2 and 10), and (4 and 5).Now plug these sets of values into the Pythagorean theorem to find the possible lengths of the hypotenuse:For (1 and 20), we get (1)² + (20)² = c², which becomes 401 = c², so c is ?401.Now do the same procedure for (2 and 10):  22 + 102 = c², so c = ?104. Perform the same procedure for (4 and 5):  42 + 52 = c², and c = ?41.</p>', 1001),
(1751, 0, 764827, 'Quant', '', '<p>If x is a positive integer, then which of the following expressions must be even?I. x(x + 5)II. (x + 2)(x + 4) III. (x + 2)(x + 5)</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q11', '<p>The correct answer is (D).Clearly, all the expressions consist of two multipliers. The first fact we use is [even × (any integer)] = even, (odd × odd) = odd. The second fact we use is (even + even) = even, (odd + odd) = even, (odd + even) = odd.  With this knowledge, let\'s study each of the 3 statements, one at a time.I. x(x + 5). If x is even, then the product is (even × odd) = even. If x is odd, then the product is (odd × even) = even. So this expression MUST be even.II. (x + 2)(x + 4). If x is even, then the expression is (even × even) = even. If x is odd, then the product is (odd × odd) = odd. Therefore this expression can be either even or odd.III. (x + 2)(x + 5). If x is even, then the product is (even × odd) = even. If x is odd, then the product is (odd × even) = even. Therefore, this expression MUST be even.Thus expressions I and III MUST be even. The correct answer is choice (D).</p>', 1001),
(1752, 0, 659260, 'Quant', '', '<p>AB = 5, BC = 12, AC = 13. Does the triangle ABC have an obtuse angle? (Angles are denoted by vertices in the answer choices).</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q12', '<p>The correct answer is (A). Obtuse angle is an angle more than 90° but less than 180°. The given triangle is a right triangle, because 5² + 12² = 13² (converse Pythagorean Theorem). Therefore it has no obtuse angles. The correct answer is A.</p>', 1001),
(1753, 0, 363298, 'Quant', '', '<p>Set A consists of the integers from 4 to 12, inclusive, while set B consists of the integers from 6 to 20, inclusive.  How many distinct integers belong to the both sets at the same time?</p>', 5, 'Test5_Sec2_Q13', '<p>The correct answer is 7. Set A and Set B are overlapping.  To determine the number overlapping elements determine the points where the overlapping begins and ends:  The sets begin to overlap at 6 and end at 12.  Between 6 and 12, inclusive, there are 7 integers.</p>', 1001),
(1754, 0, 663058, 'Quant', '', '<p>The Venn Diagram shows that, of 255 surveyed, 93 people traveled to London last year, 155 people traveled to Paris, and 70 people traveled to both locations. How many people traveled to Paris only?</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1533728926.jpg"/><br/></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q14', '<p>The correct answer is (D).  A total of 155 people traveled to Paris, which includes the 70 that traveled to both locations;  therefore, the number who went to Paris only was (155 – 70) = 85, choice (D).</p>', 1001),
(1755, 0, 222686, 'Quant', '', '<p>The Venn Diagram shows that, of 255 people surveyed, 93 people traveled to London last year, 155 people traveled to Paris, and 70 people traveled to both locations. </p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1533728943.jpg"/><br/></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q15', '<p>Let\'s break the Venn diagram into 4 non-overlapping sections.  First, we know that 70 people traveled to both cities; next we can determine that (155 – 70) = 85 people traveled to Paris only.  The number who traveled to London only was (93 – 70) = 23.  Finally, the number of people who traveled to neither city will be (255 – 70 – 85 – 23) = 77, choice (C).</p>', 1001),
(1756, 0, 883060, 'Quant', '', '<p>5 identical snow plows can clear an iced parking lot in 12 hours.  How long would it take 10 such snow plows to clear the same parking lot?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q16', '<p>The correct answer is (C). It takes a crew of 5 plows 12 hours, which is the same as saying that 1 plow, working alone, could finish the job in 12 × 5 = 60 hours.  When we put 10 plows on the job, they can do the 60 hours of required work in (60/10) = 6 hours, choice (C).</p>', 1001),
(1757, 0, 181235, 'Quant', '', '<p>Marybell takes a test consisting of 5 multiple choice questions, each with 4 answer choices (only one is correct).  She guesses at every question.  What is the probability that she will get all 5 questions correct? (round to 3 decimal places, if necessary)</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q17', '<p>The correct answer is (A).  Each question has a 1 in 4 chance of being guessed correctly, which is a probability of 0.25.  In order for Marybell to get all 5 questions correct, we multiply 0.25 times itself 5 times (because there are 5 questions on the test):  (0.25) (0.25) (0.25) (0.25) (0.25) = 0.0009765625, which rounds to 0.001, choice (A).</p>', 1001),
(1758, 0, 449807, 'Quant', '', '<p>If r is a positive integer and r is equal to 20% of 50% of the positive integer n, what is the value of r when n is equal to 400?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q18', '<p>The correct answer is (A). The first thing we must do is to create an expression relating r to n. To do this we should first convert the percentages into fractions (since fractions are easier to compute with and the percentages are simple). There should be no difficulty in converting 20% = 20/100 = 1/5 and 50% = 1/2. So then our expression for r must be r = (1/5)(1/2) n = (1/10) n.  In the next step we substitute n = 400 to determine r, so r = (1/10)(400) = 40, which is choice (A) </p>', 1001),
(1759, 0, 610068, 'Quant', '', '<p>If 221760 = n × 2ª, where n is odd, then what is the value of a?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q19', '<p>The correct answer is (D). All you need to do is to divide 221760 by 2 using the calculator until you get an odd number. a is the number of times you do division. It is 6. The correct answer is D.221760 = (3 × 3 × 5 × 7 × 11) × 64, where 64 = 2ª, a = 6.</p>', 1001);
INSERT INTO `tbl_question_new` (`id`, `noofblanks`, `trackid`, `category`, `paragraph`, `name`, `question_type_id`, `note`, `solution`, `status`) VALUES
(1760, 0, 770118, 'Quant', '', '<p>If x/y = -2, then which of the following is equivalent to x + y?</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q20', '<p>The correct answer is (-y).If x/y = -2, then we can multiply both sides of the equation by y to get x = -2y.We can then substitute -2y for x in the expression x + y, yielding the new expression -2y + y, which equals -y, which is choice (C).x + y in terms of x equals x – x/2 = x/2, which is NOT among the answer choices.</p>', 1001),
(1761, 0, 406564, 'Quant', '', '<p>In a triangle ABC, DB and DC are angle bisectors and the angle BAC = 60°. If the angle DCB is 40°, what is the degree measure of the angle DBC? (Note: The figure is not drawn to scale.)</p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q5', '<p>(D) The most important thing here is to remember that the sum of all angles of a triangle is equal to 180°. Once you assume that, the question becomes easy. We are told that the angle BAC = 60°. That leaves 120° to be split between the angles ABC and ACB. Because we know that DC and DB are angle bisectors (an angle bisector can be described as a line segment that divides an angle into two equal parts), AND we are told that the angle DCB is 40°, we can then find the value for the angle ACB by multiplying DCB by 2: 40 × 2 = 80°. Now we have the values for two of the angles in the triangle ABC: 60° + 80° = 140°, leaving 40° for the angle ABC. Knowing that DB splits ABC in half, all we have to do is to divide 40° by 2 and we get our answer: the value for DBC is 20°. The answer correct answer is D.</p>', 1001),
(1762, 0, 580141, 'Quant', '', '<p>If the point (2, -6) is the center of a circle and the point (2, 3) is on the circle, what is the circumference of the circle?</p><p><img src="http://18.218.122.78:8080/softprep//uploads/1533728906.jpg"/><br/></p>', 1, 'Test5_Sec2_Q8', '<p>You can notice that the points lie on the line, which is parallel to the y-axis, because the x-coordinate of the points is the same. So the distance between the points is 3 units from (2, 3) to the axis plus 6 units from the axis to (2, -6), making 3 + 6 = 9 units in total.Or you can use the distance formula:  d = ?[(x1 – x2)² + (y1 – y2)²], which becomes d = ?[(2 - 2)² + (-6 – 3)²], which simplifies to d = ?(0 + 81) = 9.The radius is 9. Use the circumference formula C = 2?r to get C = 2?(9) = 18?, choice (B).</p>', 1001),
(1763, 0, 421225, 'Quant', '', '<p><font color="#000000">what is video</font></p>', 1, 'video', '<p><font color="#000000">11</font></p>', 1001);
